# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: paradigms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The **actor model** in computer science is a mathematical model of concurrent computation that treats an *actor* as the basic building block of concurrent computation.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] In response to a message it receives, an actor can: make local decisions, create more actors, send more messages, and determine how to respond to the next message received.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Actors may modify their own private state, but can only affect each other indirectly through messaging (removing the need for lock-based synchronization).
[src:paradigms/actor-model] It has been used both as a framework for a theoretical understanding of computation and as the theoretical basis for several practical implementations of concurrent systems.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The relationship of the model to other work is discussed in actor model and process calculi.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] According to Carl Hewitt, unlike previous models of computation, the actor model was inspired by physics, including general relativity and quantum mechanics.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] It was also influenced by the programming languages Lisp, Simula, early versions of Smalltalk, capability-based systems, and packet switching.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Following Hewitt, Bishop, and Steiger's 1973 publication, Irene Greif developed an operational semantics for the actor model as part of her doctoral research.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Two years later, Henry Baker and Hewitt published a set of axiomatic laws for actor systems.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Other major milestones include William Clinger's 1981 dissertation introducing a denotational semantics based on power domains and Gul Agha's 1985 dissertation which further developed a transition-based semantic model complementary to Clinger's.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] This resulted in the full development of actor model theory.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Research groups led by Chuck Seitz at California Institute of Technology (Caltech) and Bill Dally at MIT constructed computer architectures that further developed the message passing in the model.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The actor model adopts the philosophy that *everything is an actor*.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] This is similar to the *everything is an object* philosophy used by some object-oriented programming languages.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] There is no assumed sequence to the above actions and they could be carried out in parallel.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Decoupling the sender from communications sent was a fundamental advance of the actor model enabling asynchronous communication and control structures as patterns of passing messages.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Recipients of messages are identified by address, sometimes called "mailing address".
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Thus an actor can only communicate with actors whose addresses it has.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] It can obtain those from a message it receives, or if the address is for an actor it has itself created.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The actor model is characterized by inherent concurrency of computation within and among actors, dynamic creation of actors, inclusion of actor addresses in messages, and interaction only through direct asynchronous message passing with no restriction on message arrival order.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Over the years, several different formal systems have been developed which permit reasoning about systems in the actor model.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The actor model can be used as a framework for modeling, understanding, and reasoning about a wide range of concurrent systems.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The actor model is about the semantics of message passing.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Arguably, the first concurrent programs were interrupt handlers.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] During the course of its normal operation a computer needed to be able to receive information from outside (characters from a keyboard, packets from a network, *etc*).
[src:paradigms/actor-model] So when the information arrived the execution of the computer was *interrupted* and special code (called an interrupt handler) was called to put the information in a data buffer where it could be subsequently retrieved.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] In the early 1960s, interrupts began to be used to simulate the concurrent execution of several programs on one processor.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Having concurrency with shared memory gave rise to the problem of concurrency control.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Originally, this problem was conceived as being one of mutual exclusion on a single computer.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra developed semaphores and later, between 1971 and 1973, Tony Hoare and Per Brinch Hansen developed monitors to solve the mutual exclusion problem.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] However, neither of these solutions provided a programming language construct that encapsulated access to shared resources.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] This encapsulation was later accomplished by the serializer construct ([Hewitt and Atkinson 1977, 1979] and [Atkinson 1980]).
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Each computational step was from one global state of the computation to the next global state.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The global state approach was continued in automata theory for finite-state machines and push down stack machines, including their nondeterministic versions.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Such nondeterministic automata have the property of bounded nondeterminism; that is, if a machine always halts when started in its initial state, then there is a bound on the number of states in which it halts.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra further developed the nondeterministic global state approach.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Hewitt argued that the actor model should provide the guarantee of service.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] In Dijkstra's model, although there could be an unbounded amount of time between the execution of sequential instructions on a computer, a (parallel) program that started out in a well defined state could terminate in only a bounded number of states [Dijkstra 1976].
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Consequently, his model could not provide the guarantee of service.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Dijkstra argued that it was impossible to implement unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Hewitt argued otherwise: there is no bound that can be placed on how long it takes a computational circuit called an *arbiter* to settle (see metastability (electronics)).
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The actor model features unbounded nondeterminism which was captured in a mathematical model by Will Clinger using domain theory.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] In the actor model, there is no global state.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Messages in the actor model are not necessarily buffered.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] This was a sharp break with previous approaches to models of concurrent computation.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The lack of buffering caused a great deal of misunderstanding at the time of the development of the actor model and is still a controversial issue.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Some researchers argued that the messages are buffered in the "ether" or the "environment".
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Also, messages in the actor model are simply sent (like packets in IP); there is no requirement for a synchronous handshake with the recipient.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] A natural development of the actor model was to allow addresses in messages.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Influenced by packet switched networks [1961 and 1964], Hewitt proposed the development of a new model of concurrent computation in which communications would not have any required fields at all: they could be empty.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Of course, if the sender of a communication desired a recipient to have access to addresses which the recipient did not already have, the address would have to be sent in the communication.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The original actor could accomplish this by sending a communication that includes the message it wishes to send, along with the address of the third actor that will handle the response.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] This third actor that will handle the response is called the *resumption* (sometimes also called a continuation or stack frame).
[src:paradigms/actor-model] When the recipient actor is ready to send a response, it sends the response message to the *resumption* actor address that was included in the original communication.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] As opposed to the previous approach based on composing sequential processes, the actor model was developed as an inherently concurrent model.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] In the actor model sequentiality was a special case that derived from concurrent computation as explained in actor model theory.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Hewitt argued against adding the requirement that messages must arrive in the order in which they are sent to the actor.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] If output message ordering is desired, then it can be modeled by a queue actor that provides this functionality.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Such a queue actor would queue the messages that arrived so that they could be retrieved in FIFO order.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] So if an actor `X` sent a message `M1` to an actor `Y`, and later `X` sent another message `M2` to `Y`, there is no requirement that `M1` arrives at `Y` before `M2`.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] In this respect the actor model mirrors packet switching systems which do not guarantee that packets must be received in the order sent.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Not providing the order of delivery guarantee allows packet switching to buffer packets, use multiple paths to send packets, resend damaged packets, and to provide other optimizations.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] For more example, actors are allowed to pipeline the processing of messages.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] What this means is that in the course of processing a message `M1`, an actor can designate the behavior to be used to process the next message, and then in fact begin processing another message `M2` before it has finished processing `M1`.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Just because an actor is allowed to pipeline the processing of messages does not mean that it *must* pipeline the processing.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Whether a message is pipelined is an engineering tradeoff.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] How would an external observer know whether the processing of a message by an actor has been pipelined?
[src:paradigms/actor-model] There is no ambiguity in the definition of an actor created by the possibility of pipelining.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Of course, it is possible to perform the pipeline optimization incorrectly in some implementations, in which case unexpected behavior may occur.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Another important characteristic of the actor model is locality.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Locality means that in processing a message, an actor can send messages only to addresses that it receives in the message, addresses that it already had before it received the message, and addresses for actors that it creates while processing the message.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Also locality means that there is no simultaneous change in multiple locations.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] In this way it differs from some other models of concurrency, *e.g.*, the Petri net model in which tokens are simultaneously removed from multiple locations and placed in other locations.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The idea of composing actor systems into larger ones is an important aspect of modularity that was developed in Gul Agha's doctoral dissertation, developed later by Gul Agha, Ian Mason, Scott Smith, and Carolyn Talcott.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] A key innovation was the introduction of *behavior* specified as a mathematical function to express what an actor does when it processes a message, including specifying a new behavior to process the next message that arrives.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Behaviors provided a mechanism to mathematically model the sharing in concurrency.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Behaviors also freed the actor model from implementation details, *e.g.*, the Smalltalk-72 token stream interpreter.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] However, the efficient implementation of systems described by the actor model require *extensive* optimization.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] See Actor model implementation for details.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Other concurrency systems (*e.g.*, process calculi) can be modeled in the actor model using a two-phase commit protocol.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] There is a *Computational Representation Theorem* in the actor model for systems which are closed in the sense that they do not receive communications from outside.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] In this way, ${\mathtt {S}}$ can be mathematically characterized in terms of all its possible behaviors (including those involving unbounded nondeterminism).
[src:paradigms/actor-model] A consequence of the above theorem is that a finite actor can nondeterministically respond with an uncountable number of different outputs.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] One of the key motivations for the development of the actor model was to understand and deal with the control structure issues that arose in development of the Planner programming language.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Once the actor model was initially defined, an important challenge was to understand the power of the model relative to Robert Kowalski's thesis that "computation can be subsumed by deduction".
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Hewitt argued that Kowalski's thesis turned out to be false for the concurrent computation in the actor model (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Nevertheless, attempts were made to extend logic programming to concurrent computation.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] However, Hewitt and Agha [1991] claimed that the resulting systems were not deductive in the following sense: computational steps of the concurrent logic programming systems do not follow deductively from previous steps (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Recently, logic programming has been integrated into the actor model in a way that maintains logical semantics.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Migration in the actor model is the ability of actors to change locations.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] *E.g.*, in his dissertation, Aki Yonezawa modeled a post office that customer actors could enter, change locations within while operating, and exit.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] An actor that can migrate can be modeled by having a location actor that changes when the actor migrates.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] However the faithfulness of this modeling is controversial and the subject of research.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] A delicate point in the actor model is the ability to synthesize the address of an actor.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] In some cases security can be used to prevent the synthesis of addresses (see Security).
[src:paradigms/actor-model] However, if an actor address is simply a bit string then clearly it can be synthesized although it may be difficult or even infeasible to guess the address of an actor if the bit strings are long enough.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] SOAP uses a URL for the address of an endpoint where an actor can be reached.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Since a URL is a character string, it can clearly be synthesized although encryption can make it virtually impossible to guess.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Synthesizing the addresses of actors is usually modeled using mapping.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The idea is to use an actor system to perform the mapping to the actual actor addresses.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] For example, on a computer the memory structure of the computer can be modeled as an actor system that does the mapping.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] In the case of SOAP addresses, it's modeling the DNS and the rest of the URL mapping.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Robin Milner's initial published work on concurrency was also notable in that it was not based on composing sequential processes.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] His work differed from the actor model because it was based on a fixed number of processes of fixed topology communicating numbers and strings using synchronous communication.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Later versions of CSP abandoned communication based on process names in favor of anonymous communication via channels, an approach also used in Milner's work on the calculus of communicating systems (CCS) and the π-calculus.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] These early models by Milner and Hoare both had the property of bounded nondeterminism.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Modern, theoretical CSP ([Hoare 1985] and [Roscoe 2005]) explicitly provides unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The actor model has been influential on both theory development and practical software development.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The actor model has influenced the development of the π-calculus and subsequent process calculi.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The actor model has had extensive influence on commercial practice.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] For example, Twitter has used actors for scalability.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Also, Microsoft has used the actor model in the development of its Asynchronous Agents Library.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] There are multiple other actor libraries listed in the actor libraries and frameworks section below.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Many of the ideas introduced in the actor model are now also finding application in multi-agent systems for these same reasons [Hewitt 2006b 2007b].
[src:paradigms/actor-model] The key difference is that agent systems (in most definitions) impose extra constraints upon the actors, typically requiring that they make use of commitments and goals.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] A number of different programming languages employ the actor model or some variation of it.
[src:paradigms/actor-model] Actor libraries or frameworks have also been implemented to permit actor-style programming in languages that don't have actors built-in.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] In computing, **aspect-oriented programming** (**AOP**) is a programming paradigm that aims to increase modularity by allowing the separation of *cross-cutting concerns*.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] It does so by adding behavior to existing code (an advice) *without* modifying the code, instead separately specifying which code is modified via a "pointcut" specification, such as "log all function calls when the function's name begins with 'set'".
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] This allows behaviors that are not central to the business logic (such as logging) to be added to a program without cluttering the code of core functions.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] AOP includes programming methods and tools that support the modularization of concerns at the level of the source code, while **aspect-oriented software development** refers to a whole engineering discipline.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Aspect-oriented programming entails breaking down program logic into cohesive areas of functionality (so-called *concerns*).
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Nearly all programming paradigms support some level of grouping and encapsulation of concerns into separate, independent entities by providing abstractions (e.g., functions, procedures, modules, classes, methods) that can be used for implementing, abstracting, and composing these concerns.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Some concerns "cut across" multiple abstractions in a program, and defy these forms of implementation.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] These concerns are called *cross-cutting concerns* or horizontal concerns.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Logging exemplifies a cross-cutting concern because a logging strategy must affect every logged part of the system.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Logging thereby *crosscuts* all logged classes and methods.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] All AOP implementations have some cross-cutting expressions that encapsulate each concern in one place.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] The difference between implementations lies in the power, safety, and usability of the constructs provided.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] For example, interceptors that specify the methods to express a limited form of cross-cutting, without much support for type-safety or debugging.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] AspectJ has a number of such expressions and encapsulates them in a special class, called an aspect.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] For example, an aspect can alter the behavior of the base code (the non-aspect part of a program) by applying advice (additional behavior) at various join points (points in a program) specified in a quantification or query called a pointcut (that detects whether a given join point matches).
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] An aspect can also make binary-compatible structural changes to other classes, such as adding members or parents.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] AOP has several direct antecedents: reflection and metaobject protocols, subject-oriented programming, Composition Filters, and Adaptive Programming.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Gregor Kiczales and colleagues at Xerox PARC developed the explicit concept of AOP and followed this with the AspectJ AOP extension to Java.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] IBM's research team pursued a tool approach over a language design approach and in 2001 proposed Hyper/J and the Concern Manipulation Environment, which have not seen wide use.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] The examples in this article use AspectJ.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] The Microsoft Transaction Server is considered to be the first major application of AOP followed by Enterprise JavaBeans.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Typically, an aspect is *scattered* or *tangled* as code, making it harder to understand and maintain.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] It is scattered by the function (such as logging) being spread over a number of unrelated functions that might use *its* function, possibly in entirely unrelated systems or written in different languages.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Thus, changing logging can require modifying all affected modules.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Aspects become tangled not only with the mainline function of the systems in which they are expressed but also with each other.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Changing one concern thus entails understanding all the tangled concerns or having some means by which the effect of changes can be inferred.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] For example, consider a banking application with a conceptually very simple method for transferring an amount from one account to another.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] In this example, other interests have become *tangled* with the basic functionality (sometimes called the *business logic concern*).
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Transactions, security, and logging all exemplify *cross-cutting concerns*.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Now consider what would happen if we suddenly need to change the security considerations for the application.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] In the program's current version, security-related operations appear *scattered* across numerous methods, and such a change would require major effort.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] AOP tries to solve this problem by allowing the programmer to express cross-cutting concerns in stand-alone modules called *aspects*.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Aspects can contain *advice* (code joined to specified points in the program) and *inter-type declarations* (structural members added to other classes).
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] For example, a security module can include advice that performs a security check before accessing a bank account.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] The pointcut defines the times (join points) when one can access a bank account, and the code in the advice body defines how the security check is implemented.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] That way, both the check and the places can be maintained in one place.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Further, a good pointcut can anticipate later program changes, so if another developer creates a new method to access the bank account, the advice will apply to the new method when it executes.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] One can think of AOP as a debugging tool or a user-level tool.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Advice should be reserved for cases in which one cannot get the function changed (user level) or do not want to change the function in production code (debugging).
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] The advice-related component of an aspect-oriented language defines a join point model (JPM).
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] A way to specify (or *quantify*) join points, called *pointcuts*.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Pointcuts determine whether a given join point matches.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Most useful pointcut languages use a syntax like the base language (for example, AspectJ uses Java signatures) and allow reuse through naming and combination.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] A means of specifying code to run at a join point.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] AspectJ calls this *advice*, and can run it before, after, and around join points.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Some implementations also support defining a method in an aspect on another class.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Join-point models can be compared based on the join points exposed, how join points are specified, the operations permitted at the join points, and the structural enhancements that can be expressed.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] All advice languages can be defined in terms of their JPM.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] This code snippet adds the `acceptVisitor` method to the `Point` class.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Any structural additions are required to be compatible with the original class, so that clients of the existing class continue to operate, unless the AOP implementation can expect to control all clients at all times.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] 2. the ultimate interpreter or environment is updated to understand and implement AOP features.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] The difficulty of changing environments means most implementations produce compatible combination programs through a type of program transformation known as *weaving*.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] An aspect weaver reads the aspect-oriented code and generates appropriate object-oriented code with the aspects integrated.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] The same AOP language can be implemented through a variety of weaving methods, so the semantics of a language should never be understood in terms of the weaving implementation.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Only the speed of an implementation and its ease of deployment are affected by the method of combination used.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Systems can implement source-level weaving using preprocessors (as C++ was implemented originally in CFront) that require access to program source files.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] However, Java's well-defined binary form enables bytecode weavers to work with any Java program in .class-file form.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Bytecode weavers can be deployed during the build process or, if the weave model is per-class, during class loading.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] AspectJ started with source-level weaving in 2001, delivered a per-class bytecode weaver in 2002, and offered advanced load-time support after the integration of AspectWerkz in 2005.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Any solution that combines programs at runtime must provide views that segregate them properly to maintain the programmer's segregated model.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Java's bytecode support for multiple source files enables any debugger to step through a properly woven .class file in a source editor.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] However, some third-party decompilers cannot process woven code because they expect code produced by Javac rather than all supported bytecode forms (see also § Criticism, below).
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Deploy-time weaving offers another approach.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] This basically implies post-processing, but rather than patching the generated code, this weaving approach *subclasses* existing classes so that the modifications are introduced by method-overriding.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] The existing classes remain untouched, even at runtime, and all existing tools, such as debuggers and profilers, can be used during development.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] A similar approach has already proven itself in the implementation of many Java EE application servers, such as IBM's WebSphere.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Even though most classes in an object-oriented model will perform a single, specific function, they often share common, secondary requirements with other classes.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] For example, we may want to add logging to classes within the data-access layer and also to classes in the UI layer whenever a thread enters or exits a method.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Even though each class has a very different primary functionality, the code needed to perform the secondary functionality is often identical.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] This is the additional code that you want to apply to your existing model.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] This refers to the point of execution in the application at which cross-cutting concern needs to be applied.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] In our example, a pointcut is reached when the thread enters a method, and another pointcut is reached when the thread exits the method.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] The combination of the pointcut and the advice is termed an aspect.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] In the example above, we add a logging aspect to our application by defining a pointcut and giving the correct advice.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Aspects emerged from object-oriented programming and reflective programming.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] AOP languages have functionality similar to, but more restricted than, metaobject protocols.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Aspects relate closely to programming concepts like subjects, mixins, and delegation.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Other ways to use aspect-oriented programming paradigms include Composition Filters and the hyperslices approach.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Since at least the 1970s, developers have been using forms of interception and dispatch-patching that resemble some of the implementation methods for AOP, but these never had the semantics that the cross-cutting specifications provide in one place.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Designers have considered alternative ways to achieve separation of code, such as C#'s partial types, but such approaches lack a quantification mechanism that allows reaching several join points of the code with one declarative statement.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Though it may seem unrelated, in testing, the use of mocks or stubs requires the use of AOP techniques, such as around advice.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Here the collaborating objects are for the purpose of the test, a cross-cutting concern.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Thus, the various Mock Object frameworks provide these features.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] For example, a process invokes a service to get a balance amount.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] In the test of the process, it is unimportant where the amount comes from, but only that the process uses the balance according to the requirements.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Programmers need to be able to read and understand code to prevent errors.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Even with proper education, understanding cross-cutting concerns can be difficult without proper support for visualizing both static structure and the dynamic flow of a program.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Starting in 2002, AspectJ began to provide IDE plug-ins to support the visualizing of cross-cutting concerns.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Those features, as well as aspect code assist and refactoring, are now common.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Given the power of AOP, making a logical mistake in expressing cross-cutting can lead to widespread program failure.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Conversely, another programmer may change the join points in a program, such as by renaming or moving methods, in ways that the aspect writer did not anticipate and with unforeseen consequences.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] One advantage of modularizing cross-cutting concerns is enabling one programmer to easily affect the entire system.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] As a result, such problems manifest as a conflict over responsibility between two or more developers for a given failure.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] AOP can expedite solving these problems, as only the aspect must be changed.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Without AOP, the corresponding problems can be much more spread out.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] The most basic criticism of the effect of AOP is that control flow is obscured, and that it is not only worse than the much-maligned GOTO statement, but is closely analogous to the joke COME FROM statement.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] The *obliviousness of application*, which is fundamental to many definitions of AOP (the code in question has no indication that an advice will be applied, which is specified instead in the pointcut), means that the advice is not visible, in contrast to an explicit method call.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Indeed, the pointcut may depend on runtime condition and thus not be statically deterministic.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] This can be mitigated but not solved by static analysis and IDE support showing which advices *potentially* match.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] General criticisms are that AOP purports to improve "both modularity and the structure of code", but some counter that it instead undermines these goals and impedes "independent development and understandability of programs".
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Cross-cutting concerns potentially cross-cut each other, requiring some resolution mechanism, such as ordering.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Indeed, aspects can apply to themselves, leading to problems such as the liar paradox.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] Technical criticisms include that the quantification of pointcuts (defining where advices are executed) is "extremely sensitive to changes in the program", which is known as the *fragile pointcut problem*.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] The problems with pointcuts are deemed intractable.
[src:paradigms/aspect-oriented-programming] If one replaces the quantification of pointcuts with explicit annotations, one obtains attribute-oriented programming instead, which is simply an explicit subroutine call and suffers the identical problem of scattering, which AOP was designed to solve.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] This is a property of a system—whether a program, computer, or a network—where there is a separate execution point or "thread of control" for each process.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] A *concurrent system* is one where a computation can advance without waiting for all other computations to complete.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing is a form of modular programming.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] In its paradigm an overall computation is factored into subcomputations that may be executed concurrently.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Pioneers in the field of concurrent computing include Edsger Dijkstra, Per Brinch Hansen, and C.A.R.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] The concept of concurrent computing is frequently confused with the related but distinct concept of parallel computing, although both can be described as "multiple processes executing *during the same period of time*".
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] By contrast, concurrent computing consists of process *lifetimes* overlapping, but execution does not happen at the same instant.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] The goal here is to model processes that happen concurrently, like multiple clients accessing a server at the same time.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Structuring software systems as composed of multiple concurrent, communicating parts can be useful for tackling complexity, regardless of whether the parts can be executed in parallel.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] In this way, multiple processes are part-way through execution at a single instant, but only one process is being executed at that instant.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computations *may* be executed in parallel, for example, by assigning each process to a separate processor or processor core, or distributing a computation across a network.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] The exact timing of when tasks in a concurrent system are executed depends on the scheduling, and tasks need not always be executed concurrently.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] The word "sequential" is used as an antonym for both "concurrent" and "parallel"; when these are explicitly distinguished, *concurrent/sequential* and *parallel/serial* are used as opposing pairs.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] A schedule in which tasks execute one at a time (serially, no parallelism), without interleaving (sequentially, no concurrency: no task begins until the prior task ends) is called a *serial schedule*.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] A set of tasks that can be scheduled serially is *serializable*, which simplifies concurrency control.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] The main challenge in designing concurrent programs is concurrency control: ensuring the correct sequencing of the interactions or communications between different computational executions, and coordinating access to resources that are shared among executions.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Potential problems include race conditions, deadlocks, and resource starvation.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Suppose `balance = 500`, and two concurrent *threads* make the calls `withdraw(300)` and `withdraw(350)`.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] If line 3 in both operations executes before line 5 both operations will find that `balance >= withdrawal` evaluates to `true`, and execution will proceed to subtracting the withdrawal amount.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] However, since both processes perform their withdrawals, the total amount withdrawn will end up being more than the original balance.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] These sorts of problems with shared resources benefit from the use of concurrency control, or non-blocking algorithms.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Introduced in 1962, Petri nets were an early attempt to codify the rules of concurrent execution.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Dataflow theory later built upon these, and Dataflow architectures were created to physically implement the ideas of dataflow theory.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Beginning in the late 1970s, process calculi such as Calculus of Communicating Systems (CCS) and Communicating Sequential Processes (CSP) were developed to permit algebraic reasoning about systems composed of interacting components.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] The π-calculus added the capability for reasoning about dynamic topologies.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Input/output automata were introduced in 1987.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Logics such as Lamport's TLA+, and mathematical models such as traces and Actor event diagrams, have also been developed to describe the behavior of concurrent systems.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Software transactional memory borrows from database theory the concept of atomic transactions and applies them to memory accesses.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages and multiprocessor programs must have a consistency model (also known as a memory model).
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] The consistency model defines rules for how operations on computer memory occur and how results are produced.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] One of the first consistency models was Leslie Lamport's sequential consistency model.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Sequential consistency is the property of a program that its execution produces the same results as a sequential program.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Specifically, a program is sequentially consistent if "the results of any execution is the same as if the operations of all the processors were executed in some sequential order, and the operations of each individual processor appear in this sequence in the order specified by its program".
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] A number of different methods can be used to implement concurrent programs, such as implementing each computational execution as an operating system process, or implementing the computational processes as a set of threads within a single operating system process.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] In some concurrent computing systems, communication between the concurrent components is hidden from the programmer (e.g., by using futures), while in others it must be handled explicitly.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] The exchange of messages may be carried out asynchronously, or may use a synchronous "rendezvous" style in which the sender blocks until the message is received.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Asynchronous message passing may be reliable or unreliable (sometimes referred to as "send and pray").
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Message-passing concurrency tends to be far easier to reason about than shared-memory concurrency, and is typically considered a more robust form of concurrent programming.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Shared memory and message passing concurrency have different performance characteristics.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Typically (although not always), the per-process memory overhead and task switching overhead is lower in a message passing system, but the overhead of message passing is greater than for a procedure call.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] These differences are often overwhelmed by other performance factors.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing developed out of earlier work on railroads and telegraphy, from the 19th and early 20th century, and some terms date to this period, such as semaphores.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] These arose to address the question of how to handle multiple trains on the same railroad system (avoiding collisions and maximizing efficiency) and how to handle multiple transmissions over a given set of wires (improving efficiency), such as via time-division multiplexing (1870s).
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] The academic study of concurrent algorithms started in the 1960s, with Dijkstra (1965) credited with being the first paper in this field, identifying and solving mutual exclusion.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Concurrency is pervasive in computing, occurring from low-level hardware on a single chip to worldwide networks.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] At the network level, networked systems are generally concurrent by their nature, as they consist of separate devices.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages are programming languages that use language constructs for concurrency.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] These constructs may involve multi-threading, support for distributed computing, message passing, shared resources (including shared memory) or futures and promises.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Such languages are sometimes described as *concurrency-oriented languages* or *concurrency-oriented programming languages* (COPL).
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Today, the most commonly used programming languages that have specific constructs for concurrency are Java and C#.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Both of these languages fundamentally use a shared-memory concurrency model, with locking provided by monitors (although message-passing models can and have been implemented on top of the underlying shared-memory model).
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Of the languages that use a message-passing concurrency model, Erlang was probably the most widely used in industry as of 2010.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Many concurrent programming languages have been developed more as research languages (e.g., Pict) rather than as languages for production use.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] However, languages such as Erlang, Limbo, and occam have seen industrial use at various times in the last 20 years.
[src:paradigms/concurrent-computing] Many other languages provide support for concurrency in the form of libraries, at levels roughly comparable with the above list.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] In computer programming, **dataflow programming** is a programming paradigm that models a program as a directed graph of the data flowing between operations, thus implementing dataflow principles and architecture.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programming languages share some features of functional languages, and were generally developed in order to bring some functional concepts to a language more suitable for numeric processing.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Some authors use the term *datastream* instead of *dataflow* to avoid confusion with dataflow computing or dataflow architecture, based on an indeterministic machine paradigm.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programming was pioneered by Jack Dennis and his graduate students at MIT in the 1960s.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Traditionally, a program is modelled as a series of operations happening in a specific order; this may be referred to as sequential, procedural, control flow (indicating that the program chooses a specific path), or imperative programming.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] The program focuses on commands, in line with the von Neumann vision of sequential programming, where data is normally "at rest".
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] In contrast, dataflow programming emphasizes the movement of data and models programs as a series of connections.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Explicitly defined inputs and outputs connect operations, which function like black boxes.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] An operation runs as soon as all of its inputs become valid.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Thus, dataflow languages are inherently parallel and can work well in large, decentralized systems.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] One of the key concepts in computer programming is the idea of state, essentially a snapshot of various conditions in the system.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Most programming languages require a considerable amount of state information, which is generally hidden from the programmer.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Often, the computer itself has no idea which piece of information encodes the enduring state.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] This is a serious problem, as the state information needs to be shared across multiple processors in parallel processing machines.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Most languages force the programmer to add extra code to indicate which data and parts of the code are important to the state.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] This code tends to be both expensive in terms of performance, as well as difficult to read or debug.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Explicit parallelism is one of the main reasons for the poor performance of Enterprise Java Beans when building data-intensive, non-OLTP applications.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Where a sequential program can be imagined as a single worker moving between tasks (operations), a dataflow program is more like a series of workers on an assembly line, each doing a specific task whenever materials are available.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Since the operations are only concerned with the availability of data inputs, they have no hidden state to track, and are all "ready" at the same time.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programs are represented in different ways.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] A traditional program is usually represented as a series of text instructions, which is reasonable for describing a serial system which pipes data between small, single-purpose tools that receive, process, and return.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programs start with an input, perhaps the command line parameters, and illustrate how that data is used and modified.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] The flow of data is explicit, often visually illustrated as a line or pipe.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] In terms of encoding, a dataflow program might be implemented as a hash table, with uniquely identified inputs as the keys, used to look up pointers to the instructions.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] When any operation completes, the program scans down the list of operations until it finds the first operation where all inputs are currently valid, and runs it.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] When that operation finishes, it will typically output data, thereby making another operation become valid.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] For parallel operation, only the list needs to be shared; it is the state of the entire program.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Thus the task of maintaining state is removed from the programmer and given to the language's runtime.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] On machines with a single processor core where an implementation designed for parallel operation would simply introduce overhead, this overhead can be removed completely by using a different runtime.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Some recent dataflow libraries such as Differential/Timely Dataflow have used incremental computing for much more efficient data processing.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] A pioneer dataflow language was BLOck DIagram (BLODI), published in 1961 by John Larry Kelly, Jr., Carol Lochbaum and Victor A.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Vyssotsky for specifying sampled data systems.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] A BLODI specification of functional units (amplifiers, adders, delay lines, etc.) and their interconnections was compiled into a single loop that updated the entire system for one clock tick.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] In a 1966 Ph.D. thesis, *The On-line Graphical Specification of Computer Procedures*, Bert Sutherland created one of the first graphical dataflow programming frameworks in order to make parallel programming easier.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Subsequent dataflow languages were often developed at the large supercomputer labs.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] SISAL, a popular dataflow language developed at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, looks like most statement-driven languages, but variables should be assigned once.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] This allows the compiler to easily identify the inputs and outputs.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] A number of offshoots of SISAL have been developed, including SAC, *Single Assignment C*, which tries to remain as close to the popular C programming language as possible.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] The United States Navy funded development of signal processing graph notation (SPGN) and ACOS starting in the early 1980s.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] This is in use on a number of platforms in the field today.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] A more radical concept is Prograph, in which programs are constructed as graphs onscreen, and variables are replaced entirely with lines linking inputs to outputs.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] Prograph was originally written on the Macintosh, which remained single-processor until the introduction of the DayStar Genesis MP in 1996.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] There are many hardware architectures oriented toward the efficient implementation of dataflow programming models.
[src:paradigms/dataflow-programming] MIT's tagged token dataflow architecture was designed by Greg Papadopoulos.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] In computer science, **declarative programming** is a programming paradigm that expresses the logic of a computation without fully describing its control flow.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] This is in contrast with imperative programming, which implements algorithms in explicit steps.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Declarative programming may consider programs as theories of a formal logic, and computations as deductions in that logical theory.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Declarative programming at times simplifies the writing of parallel programs.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Common declarative language paradigms include logic programming (e.g., Prolog, Datalog, answer set programming), and algebraic modeling systems.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is often defined as any style of programming that is not imperative.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] A number of other common definitions attempt to define it by simply contrasting it with imperative programming.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] These definitions overlap substantially.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is a non-imperative style of programming in which programs describe their desired results without explicitly listing commands or steps that must be performed.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages are characterized by a mostly declarative programming style.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] In logic programming, programs consist of sentences expressed in logical form, and computation uses those sentences to solve problems, which are also expressed in logical form.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] In a pure functional language, such as Haskell, all functions are without side effects, and state changes are only represented as functions that transform the state, which is explicitly represented as a first-class object in the program.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Although pure functional languages are non-imperative, they often provide a facility for describing the effect of a function as a series of steps.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Other functional languages, such as Lisp, OCaml and Erlang, support a mixture of procedural and functional programming.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Some logic programming languages, such as Prolog, and database query languages, such as SQL, while declarative in principle, also support a procedural style of programming.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is an umbrella term that includes a number of better-known programming paradigms.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Constraint programming states relations between variables in the form of constraints that specify the properties of the target solution.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] The set of constraints is solved by giving a value to each variable so that the solution is consistent with the maximum number of constraints.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Constraint programming often complements other paradigms: functional, logical, or even imperative programming.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Makefiles, for example, specify dependencies in a declarative fashion, but include an imperative list of actions to take as well.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Similarly, yacc specifies a context free grammar declaratively, but includes code snippets from a host language, which is usually imperative (such as C).
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages, such as Prolog, Datalog and answer set programming, compute by proving that a goal is a logical consequence of the program, or by showing that the goal is true in a model defined by the program.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Prolog computes by reducing goals to subgoals, top-down using backward reasoning, whereas most Datalog systems compute bottom-up using forward reasoning.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Answer set programs typically use SAT solvers to generate a model of the program.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Models, or mathematical representations, of physical systems may be implemented in computer code that is declarative.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] The code contains a number of equations, not imperative assignments, that describe ("declare") the behavioral relationships.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] When a model is expressed in this formalism, a computer is able to perform algebraic manipulations to best formulate the solution algorithm.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] The mathematical causality is typically imposed at the boundaries of the physical system, while the behavioral description of the system itself is declarative or acausal.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Declarative modeling languages and environments include Analytica, Modelica and Simile.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Prolog (1972) stands for "PROgramming in LOGic." It was developed for natural language question answering, using SL resolution both to deduce answers to queries and to parse and generate natural language sentences.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] The building blocks of a Prolog program are *facts* and *rules*.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Given this program, the query `eat(tom,jerry)` succeeds, while `eat(jerry,tom)` fails.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Moreover, the query `eat(X,jerry)` succeeds with the answer substitution `X=tom`.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Prolog executes programs top-down, using SLD resolution to reason backwards, reducing goals to subgoals.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] In this example, it uses the last rule of the program to reduce the goal of answering the query `eat(X,jerry)` to the subgoals of first finding an X such that `big(X)` holds and then of showing that `small(jerry)` holds.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] It repeatedly uses rules to further reduce subgoals to other subgoals, until it eventually succeeds in unifying all subgoals with facts in the program.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] This backward reasoning, goal-reduction strategy treats rules in logic programs as procedures, and makes Prolog both a declarative and procedural programming language.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] The broad range of Prolog applications is highlighted in the Year of Prolog Book, celebrating the 50 year anniversary of Prolog.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] The origins of Datalog date back to the beginning of logic programming, but it was identified as a separate area around 1977.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Syntactically and semantically, it is a subset of Prolog.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] But because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Most Datalog systems execute programs bottom-up, using rules to reason forwards, deriving new facts from existing facts, and terminating when there are no new facts that can be derived, or when the derived facts unify with the query.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Datalog has been applied to such problems as data integration, information extraction, networking, security, cloud computing and machine learning.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Answer set programming (ASP) evolved in the late 1990s, based on the stable model (answer set) semantics of logic programming.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Like Datalog, it is a subset of Prolog; and, because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Most implementations of ASP execute a program by first *grounding* the program, replacing all variables in rules by constants in all possible ways, and then using a propositional SAT solver, such as the DPLL algorithm to generate one or more models of the program.
[src:paradigms/declarative-programming] Its applications are oriented towards solving difficult search problems and knowledge representation.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] In computer programming, **event-driven programming** is a programming paradigm in which the flow of the program is determined by external events.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] User interface (UI) events from keyboards and mice, touchpads and touchscreens, and external sensor inputs are common cases.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] Events may also be programmatically generated, such as from messages from other programs, notifications from other threads, or other network events.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programming is the dominant paradigm used in graphical user interface (GUI) applications and network servers.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] In an event-driven application, there is generally an event loop that listens for events and then triggers a callback function when one of those events is detected.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programs can be written in any programming language, although the task is easier in languages that provide high-level abstractions.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] Although they do not exactly fit the event-driven model, interrupt handling and exception handling have many similarities.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] It is important to differentiate between event-driven and message-driven (aka queue-driven) paradigms: event-driven services (e.g.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] AWS SNS) are decoupled from their consumers, whereas message/queue-driven services (e.g.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] AWS SQS) are coupled with their consumers.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] Because the event loop that retrieves and dispatches events is common amongst applications, many programming frameworks provide an implementation of an event loop, and the application developer only needs to write the event handlers.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] The actual logic is contained in event handler routines.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] These routines handle the events to which the main program will respond.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] For example, a single mouse-click on a "Save" command button in a GUI program might trigger a routine to save data to a database.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] An "Exit" button might trigger a routine to exit the program.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] The event loop receives events from all such command buttons and other GUI elements, dispatching the appropriate event handler routine for each button.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] Event handler routines need to be bound to specific events, so the event loop can dispatch the correct routine in response to the event.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] Many IDEs simplify this process by providing the programmer with an event handling template for each specific event (such as a button click), allowing the programmer to focus on writing the event-handling code.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] In a sequential program, keeping track of execution order and history is normally trivial.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] But in an event-driven program, event handlers execute non-sequentially in response to external events.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] Special attention and planning is required to correctly structure the event handlers to work when called in any order.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] Most existing GUI architectures use event-driven programming.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] The Java AWT framework processes all UI changes on a single thread, called the Event dispatching thread.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] Similarly, all UI updates in the Java framework JavaFX occur on the JavaFX Application Thread.
[src:paradigms/event-driven-programming] Most network servers and frameworks such as Node.js are also event-driven.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In computer science, **functional programming** is a programming paradigm where programs are constructed by applying and composing functions.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] It is a declarative programming paradigm in which function definitions are trees of expressions that map values to other values, rather than a sequence of imperative statements which update the running state of the program.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In functional programming, functions are treated as first-class entities, meaning that they can be bound to names (including local identifiers), passed as arguments, and returned from other functions, just as any other data type can.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] This allows programs to be written in a declarative and composable style, where small functions are combined in a modular manner.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional programming is sometimes treated as synonymous with purely functional programming, a subset of functional programming that treats all functions as deterministic mathematical functions, or pure functions.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] When a pure function is called with some given arguments, it will always return the same result, and cannot be affected by any mutable state or other side effects.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] This is in contrast with impure procedures, common in imperative programming, which can have side effects (such as modifying the program's state or taking input from a user).
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Proponents of purely functional programming claim that by restricting side effects, programs can have fewer bugs, be easier to debug and test, and be more suited to formal verification.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional programming has its roots in academia, evolving from the lambda calculus, a formal system of computation based only on functions.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional programming has historically been less popular than imperative programming, but many functional languages are seeing use today in industry and education, including Common Lisp, Scheme, Clojure, Wolfram Language, Racket, Erlang, Elixir, OCaml, Haskell, and F#.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Lean is a functional programming language commonly used for verifying mathematical theorems.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional programming is also key to some languages that have found success in specific domains, like JavaScript in the Web, R in statistics, J, K and Q in financial analysis, and XQuery/XSLT for XML.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Domain-specific declarative languages like SQL and Lex/Yacc use some elements of functional programming, such as not allowing mutable values.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In addition, many other programming languages support programming in a functional style or have implemented features from functional programming, such as C++ (since C++11), C#, Kotlin, Perl, PHP, Python, Go, Rust, Raku, Scala, and Java (since Java 8).
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] The lambda calculus, developed in the 1930s by Alonzo Church, is a formal system of computation built from function application.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In 1937 Alan Turing proved that the lambda calculus and Turing machines are equivalent models of computation, showing that the lambda calculus is Turing complete.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Lambda calculus forms the basis of all functional programming languages.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] An equivalent theoretical formulation, combinatory logic, was developed by Moses Schönfinkel and Haskell Curry in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Church later developed a weaker system, the simply typed lambda calculus, which extended the lambda calculus by assigning a data type to all terms.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] This forms the basis for statically typed functional programming.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] The first high-level functional programming language, Lisp, was developed in the late 1950s for the IBM 700/7000 series of scientific computers by John McCarthy while at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Lisp functions were defined using Church's lambda notation, extended with a label construct to allow recursive functions.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Lisp first introduced many paradigmatic features of functional programming, though early Lisps were multi-paradigm languages, and incorporated support for numerous programming styles as new paradigms evolved.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Later dialects, such as Scheme and Clojure, and offshoots such as Dylan and Julia, sought to simplify and rationalise Lisp around a cleanly functional core, while Common Lisp was designed to preserve and update the paradigmatic features of the numerous older dialects it replaced.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Information Processing Language (IPL), 1956, is sometimes cited as the first computer-based functional programming language.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] It is an assembly-style language for manipulating lists of symbols.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] It does have a notion of *generator*, which amounts to a function that accepts a function as an argument, and, since it is a low-level programming language, code can be data, so IPL can be regarded as having higher-order functions.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] However, it relies heavily on the mutating list structure and similar imperative features.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Iverson developed APL in the early 1960s, described in his 1962 book *A Programming Language* (ISBN 9780471430148).
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] APL was the primary influence on John Backus's FP.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In the early 1990s, Iverson and Roger Hui created J.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In the mid-1990s, Arthur Whitney, who had previously worked with Iverson, created K, which is used commercially in financial industries along with its descendant Q.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In the mid-1960s, Peter Landin invented SECD machine, the first abstract machine for a functional programming language, described a correspondence between ALGOL 60 and the lambda calculus, and proposed the ISWIM programming language.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] John Backus presented FP in his 1977 Turing Award lecture "Can Programming Be Liberated From the von Neumann Style?
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] A Functional Style and its Algebra of Programs".
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] He defines functional programs as being built up in a hierarchical way by means of "combining forms" that allow an "algebra of programs"; in modern language, this means that functional programs follow the principle of compositionality.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Backus's paper popularized research into functional programming, though it emphasized function-level programming rather than the lambda-calculus style now associated with functional programming.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] The 1973 language ML was created by Robin Milner at the University of Edinburgh, and David Turner developed the language SASL at the University of St Andrews.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Also in Edinburgh in the 1970s, Burstall and Darlington developed the functional language NPL.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] NPL was based on Kleene Recursion Equations and was first introduced in their work on program transformation.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Burstall, MacQueen and Sannella then incorporated the polymorphic type checking from ML to produce the language Hope.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] ML eventually developed into several dialects, the most common of which are now OCaml and Standard ML.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Steele and Gerald Jay Sussman developed Scheme, as described in the Lambda Papers and the 1985 textbook *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs*.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Scheme was the first dialect of lisp to use lexical scoping and to require tail-call optimization, features that encourage functional programming.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In the 1980s, Per Martin-Löf developed intuitionistic type theory (also called *constructive* type theory), which associated functional programs with constructive proofs expressed as dependent types.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] This led to new approaches to interactive theorem proving and has influenced the development of subsequent functional programming languages.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] The lazy functional language, Miranda, developed by David Turner, initially appeared in 1985 and had a strong influence on Haskell.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] With Miranda being proprietary, Haskell began with a consensus in 1987 to form an open standard for functional programming research; implementation releases have been ongoing as of 1990.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] More recently it has found use in niches such as parametric CAD in the OpenSCAD language built on the CGAL framework, although its restriction on reassigning values (all values are treated as constants) has led to confusion among users who are unfamiliar with functional programming as a concept.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional programming continues to be used in commercial settings.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] A number of concepts and paradigms are specific to functional programming, and generally foreign to imperative programming (including object-oriented programming).
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] However, programming languages often cater to several programming paradigms, so programmers using "mostly imperative" languages may have utilized some of these concepts.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Higher-order functions are functions that can either take other functions as arguments or return them as results.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In calculus, an example of a higher-order function is the differential operator $d/dx$ , which returns the derivative of a function f .
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Higher-order functions are closely related to first-class functions in that higher-order functions and first-class functions both allow functions as arguments and results of other functions.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Higher-order functions enable partial application or currying, a technique that applies a function to its arguments one at a time, with each application returning a new function that accepts the next argument.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] This lets a programmer succinctly express, for example, the successor function as the addition operator partially applied to the natural number one.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Pure functions (or expressions) have no side effects (memory or I/O).
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Some compilers, such as gcc, add extra keywords for a programmer to explicitly mark external functions as pure, to enable such optimizations.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Fortran 95 also lets functions be designated *pure*.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] C++11 added `constexpr` keyword with similar semantics.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Iteration (looping) in functional languages is usually accomplished via recursion.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Recursive functions invoke themselves, letting an operation be repeated until it reaches the base case.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In general, recursion requires maintaining a stack, which consumes space in a linear amount to the depth of recursion.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] This could make recursion prohibitively expensive to use instead of imperative loops.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] However, a special form of recursion known as tail recursion can be recognized and optimized by a compiler into the same code used to implement iteration in imperative languages.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Tail recursion optimization can be implemented by transforming the program into continuation passing style during compiling, among other approaches.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] The Scheme language standard requires implementations to support proper tail recursion, meaning they must allow an unbounded number of active tail calls.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Proper tail recursion is not simply an optimization; it is a language feature that assures users that they can use recursion to express a loop and doing so would be safe-for-space.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Moreover, contrary to its name, it accounts for all tail calls, not just tail recursion.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] While proper tail recursion is usually implemented by turning code into imperative loops, implementations might implement it in other ways.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] For example, Chicken intentionally maintains a stack and lets the stack overflow.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] However, when this happens, its garbage collector will claim space back, allowing an unbounded number of active tail calls even though it does not turn tail recursion into a loop.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Common patterns of recursion can be abstracted away using higher-order functions, with catamorphisms and anamorphisms (or "folds" and "unfolds") being the most obvious examples.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Such recursion schemes play a role analogous to built-in control structures such as loops in imperative languages.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Some special purpose languages such as Rocq allow only well-founded recursion and are strongly normalizing (nonterminating computations can be expressed only with infinite streams of values called codata).
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] As a consequence, these languages fail to be Turing complete and expressing certain functions in them is impossible, but they can still express a wide class of interesting computations while avoiding the problems introduced by unrestricted recursion.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional programming limited to well-founded recursion with a few other constraints is called total functional programming.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional languages can be categorized by whether they use *strict (eager)* or *non-strict (lazy)* evaluation, concepts that refer to how function arguments are processed when an expression is being evaluated.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] The technical difference is in the denotational semantics of expressions containing failing or divergent computations.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Under strict evaluation, the evaluation of any term containing a failing subterm fails.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] fails under strict evaluation because of the division by zero in the third element of the list.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Under lazy evaluation, the length function returns the value 4 (i.e., the number of items in the list), since evaluating it does not attempt to evaluate the terms making up the list.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In brief, strict evaluation always fully evaluates function arguments before invoking the function.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Lazy evaluation does not evaluate function arguments unless their values are required to evaluate the function call itself.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] The usual implementation strategy for lazy evaluation in functional languages is graph reduction.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Lazy evaluation is used by default in several pure functional languages, including Miranda, Clean, and Haskell.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Hughes 1984 argues for lazy evaluation as a mechanism for improving program modularity through separation of concerns, by easing independent implementation of producers and consumers of data streams.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Launchbury 1993 describes some difficulties that lazy evaluation introduces, particularly in analyzing a program's storage requirements, and proposes an operational semantics to aid in such analysis.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Harper 2009 proposes including both strict and lazy evaluation in the same language, using the language's type system to distinguish them.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Some research-oriented functional languages such as Rocq, Agda, Cayenne, and Epigram are based on intuitionistic type theory, which lets types depend on terms.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] These type systems do not have decidable type inference and are difficult to understand and program with.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] But dependent types can express arbitrary propositions in higher-order logic.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Through the Curry–Howard isomorphism, then, well-typed programs in these languages become a means of writing formal mathematical proofs from which a compiler can generate certified code.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] While these languages are mainly of interest in academic research (including in formalized mathematics), they have begun to be used in engineering as well.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Compcert is a compiler for a subset of the language C that is written in Rocq and formally verified.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] A limited form of dependent types called generalized algebraic data types (GADT's) can be implemented in a way that provides some of the benefits of dependently typed programming while avoiding most of its inconvenience.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] GADT's are available in the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, in OCaml and in Scala, and have been proposed as additions to other languages including Java and C#.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional programs do not have assignment statements, that is, the value of a variable in a functional program never changes once defined.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] This eliminates any chances of side effects because any variable can be replaced with its actual value at any point of execution.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] So, functional programs are referentially transparent.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Consider C assignment statement `x = x * 10`, this changes the value assigned to the variable `x`.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Let us say that the initial value of `x` was `1`, then two consecutive evaluations of the variable `x` yields `10` and `100` respectively.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Clearly, replacing `x = x * 10` with either `10` or `100` gives a program a different meaning, and so the expression *is not* referentially transparent.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In fact, assignment statements are never referentially transparent.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Now, consider another function such as `int plusOne(int x) { return x + 1; }` *is* transparent, as it does not implicitly change the input x and thus has no such side effects.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional programs exclusively use this type of function and are therefore referentially transparent.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are often represented in a different way to their imperative counterparts.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] For example, the array with constant access and update times is a basic component of most imperative languages, and many imperative data-structures, such as the hash table and binary heap, are based on arrays.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Arrays can be replaced by maps or random access lists, which admit purely functional implementation, but have logarithmic access and update times.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Purely functional data structures have persistence, a property of keeping previous versions of the data structure unmodified.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In Clojure, persistent data structures are used as functional alternatives to their imperative counterparts.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Persistent vectors, for example, use trees for partial updating.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Calling the insert method will result in some but not all nodes being created.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional programming is very different from imperative programming.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] The most significant differences stem from the fact that functional programming avoids side effects, which are used in imperative programming to implement state and I/O.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Pure functional programming completely prevents side-effects and provides referential transparency.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Higher-order functions are rarely used in older imperative programming.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] A traditional imperative program might use a loop to traverse and modify a list.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] A functional program, on the other hand, would probably use a higher-order "map" function that takes a function and a list, generating and returning a new list by applying the function to each list item.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] The following two examples (written in Java) achieve the same effect: they multiply all even numbers in an array by 10 and add them all, storing the final sum in the variable `result`.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Sometimes the abstractions offered by functional programming might lead to development of more robust code that avoids certain issues that might arise when building upon large amount of complex, imperative code, such as off-by-one errors (see Greenspun's tenth rule).
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] There are tasks (for example, maintaining a bank account balance) that often seem most naturally implemented with state.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Pure functional programming performs these tasks, and I/O tasks such as accepting user input and printing to the screen, in a different way.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] The pure functional programming language Haskell implements them using monads, derived from category theory.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Monads offer a way to abstract certain types of computational patterns, including (but not limited to) modeling of computations with mutable state (and other side effects such as I/O) in an imperative manner without losing purity.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] While existing monads may be easy to apply in a program, given appropriate templates and examples, many students find them difficult to understand conceptually, e.g., when asked to define new monads (which is sometimes needed for certain types of libraries).
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional languages also simulate states by passing around immutable states.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] This can be done by making a function accept the state as one of its parameters, and return a new state together with the result, leaving the old state unchanged.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Impure functional languages usually include a more direct method of managing mutable state.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Clojure, for example, uses managed references that can be updated by applying pure functions to the current state.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] This kind of approach enables mutability while still promoting the use of pure functions as the preferred way to express computations.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Alternative methods such as Hoare logic and uniqueness have been developed to track side effects in programs.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Some modern research languages use effect systems to make the presence of side effects explicit.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional programming languages are typically less efficient in their use of CPU and memory than imperative languages such as C and Pascal.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] This is related to the fact that some mutable data structures like arrays have a very straightforward implementation using present hardware.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Flat arrays may be accessed very efficiently with deeply pipelined CPUs, prefetched efficiently through caches (with no complex pointer chasing), or handled with SIMD instructions.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] It is also not easy to create their equally efficient general-purpose immutable counterparts.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] For purely functional languages, the worst-case slowdown is logarithmic in the number of memory cells used, because mutable memory can be represented by a purely functional data structure with logarithmic access time (such as a balanced tree).
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] However, such slowdowns are not universal.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] For programs that perform intensive numerical computations, functional languages such as OCaml and Clean are only slightly slower than C according to The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] For programs that handle large matrices and multidimensional databases, array functional languages (such as J and K) were designed with speed optimizations.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Immutability of data can in many cases lead to execution efficiency by allowing the compiler to make assumptions that are unsafe in an imperative language, thus increasing opportunities for inline expansion.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Even if the involved copying that may seem implicit when dealing with persistent immutable data structures might seem computationally costly, some functional programming languages, like Clojure solve this issue by implementing mechanisms for safe memory sharing between *formally* *immutable* data.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] This is how for example `java.util.concurrent` classes are implemented, where some of them are immutable variants of the corresponding classes that are not suitable for concurrent use.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional programming languages often have a concurrency model that instead of shared state and synchronization, leverages message passing mechanisms (such as the actor model, where each actor is a container for state, behavior, child actors and a message queue).
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] This approach is common in Erlang/Elixir or Akka.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Lazy evaluation may also speed up the program, even asymptotically, whereas it may slow it down at most by a constant factor (however, it may introduce memory leaks if used improperly).
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Launchbury 1993 discusses theoretical issues related to memory leaks from lazy evaluation, and O'Sullivan *et al.* 2008 give some practical advice for analyzing and fixing them.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] However, the most general implementations of lazy evaluation making extensive use of dereferenced code and data perform poorly on modern processors with deep pipelines and multi-level caches (where a cache miss may cost hundreds of cycles).
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Some functional programming languages might not optimize abstractions such as higher order functions like "map" or "filter" as efficiently as the underlying imperative operations.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] has the mean execution time of 4.76 ms, while the second one, in which `.equals` is a direct invocation of the underlying Java method, has a mean execution time of 2.8 μs – roughly 1700 times faster.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Part of that can be attributed to the type checking and exception handling involved in the implementation of `even?`.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] For instance the lo library for Go, which implements various higher-order functions common in functional programming languages using generics.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In a benchmark provided by the library's author, calling `map` is 4% slower than an equivalent `for` loop and has the same allocation profile, which can be attributed to various compiler optimizations, such as inlining.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] One distinguishing feature of Rust are *zero-cost abstractions*.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] This means that using them imposes no additional runtime overhead.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] This is achieved thanks to the compiler using loop unrolling, where each iteration of a loop, be it imperative or using iterators, is converted into a standalone Assembly instruction, without the overhead of the loop controlling code.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] If an iterative operation writes to an array, the resulting array's elements will be stored in specific CPU registers, allowing for constant-time access at runtime.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] It is possible to use a functional style of programming in languages that are not traditionally considered functional languages.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] For example, both D and Fortran 95 explicitly support pure functions.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] JavaScript, Lua, Python and Go had first class functions from their inception.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Python had support for "lambda", "map", "reduce", and "filter" in 1994, as well as closures in Python 2.2, though Python 3 relegated "reduce" to the `functools` standard library module.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] First-class functions have been introduced into other mainstream languages such as Perl 5.0 in 1994, PHP 5.3, Visual Basic 9, C# 3.0, C++11, and Kotlin.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In Perl, lambda, map, reduce, filter, and closures are fully supported and frequently used.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] The book Higher-Order Perl, released in 2005, was written to provide an expansive guide on using Perl for functional programming.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In PHP, anonymous classes, closures and lambdas are fully supported.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Libraries and language extensions for immutable data structures are being developed to aid programming in the functional style.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In Java, anonymous classes can sometimes be used to simulate closures; however, anonymous classes are not always proper replacements to closures because they have more limited capabilities.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Java 8 supports lambda expressions as a replacement for some anonymous classes.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In C#, anonymous classes are not necessary, because closures and lambdas are fully supported.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Libraries and language extensions for immutable data structures are being developed to aid programming in the functional style in C#.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Many object-oriented design patterns are expressible in functional programming terms: for example, the strategy pattern simply dictates use of a higher-order function, and the visitor pattern roughly corresponds to a catamorphism, or fold.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Similarly, the idea of immutable data from functional programming is often included in imperative programming languages, for example the tuple in Python, which is an immutable array, and Object.freeze() in JavaScript.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Logic programming can be viewed as a generalisation of functional programming, in which functions are a special case of relations.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] For example, the function, mother(X) = Y, (every X has only one mother Y) can be represented by the relation mother(X, Y).
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Whereas functions have a strict input-output pattern of arguments, relations can be queried with any pattern of inputs and outputs.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Compared with relational syntax, functional syntax is a more compact notation for nested functions.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] However, the difference between the two representations is simply syntactic.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Ciao transforms the function-like notation into relational form and executes the resulting logic program using the standard Prolog execution strategy.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Emacs, a highly extensible text editor family uses its own Lisp dialect for writing plugins.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] The original author of the most popular Emacs implementation, GNU Emacs and Emacs Lisp, Richard Stallman considers Lisp one of his favorite programming languages.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Spreadsheets can be considered a form of pure, zeroth-order, strict-evaluation functional programming system.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] However, spreadsheets generally lack higher-order functions as well as code reuse, and in some implementations, also lack recursion.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Several extensions have been developed for spreadsheet programs to enable higher-order and reusable functions, but so far remain primarily academic in nature.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Due to their composability, functional programming paradigms can be suitable for microservices-based architectures.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional programming is an active area of research in the field of programming language theory.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] There are several peer-reviewed publication venues focusing on functional programming, including the International Conference on Functional Programming, the Journal of Functional Programming, and the Symposium on Trends in Functional Programming.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional programming has been employed in a wide range of industrial applications.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Scheme, a dialect of Lisp, was used as the basis for several applications on early Apple Macintosh computers and has been applied to problems such as training-simulation software and telescope control.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] OCaml, which was introduced in the mid-1990s, has seen commercial use in areas such as financial analysis, driver verification, industrial robot programming and static analysis of embedded software.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Haskell, though initially intended as a research language, has also been applied in areas such as aerospace systems, hardware design and web programming.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Other functional programming languages that have seen use in industry include Scala, F#, Wolfram Language, Lisp, Standard ML and Clojure.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Scala has been widely used in Data science, while ClojureScript, Elm or PureScript are some of the functional frontend programming languages used in production.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional "platforms" have been popular in finance for risk analytics (particularly with large investment banks).
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Risk factors are coded as functions that form interdependent graphs (categories) to measure correlations in market shifts, similar in manner to Gröbner basis optimizations but also for regulatory frameworks such as Comprehensive Capital Analysis and Review.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Given the use of OCaml and Caml variations in finance, these systems are sometimes considered related to a categorical abstract machine.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Functional programming is heavily influenced by category theory.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Many universities teach functional programming.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Some treat it as an introductory programming concept while others first teach imperative programming methods.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] Outside of computer science, functional programming is used to teach problem-solving, algebraic and geometric concepts.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] It has also been used to teach classical mechanics, as in the book *Structure and Interpretation of Classical Mechanics*.
[src:paradigms/functional-programming] In particular, Scheme has been a relatively popular choice for teaching programming for years.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Generic programming was introduced to the mainstream with Ada in 1977.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] With templates in C++, generic programming became part of the repertoire of professional library design.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The techniques were further improved and *parameterized types* were introduced in the influential 1994 book *Design Patterns*.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] New techniques were introduced by Andrei Alexandrescu in his 2001 book *Modern C++ Design: Generic Programming and Design Patterns Applied*.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Subsequently, D implemented the same ideas.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Such software entities are known as *generics* in Ada, C#, Delphi, Eiffel, F#, Java, Mojo, Nim, Python, Go, Rust, Swift, TypeScript, and Visual Basic (.NET).
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] They are known as *parametric polymorphism* in ML, Scala, Julia, and Haskell.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The "generic programming" paradigm is an approach to software decomposition whereby fundamental requirements on types are abstracted from across concrete examples of algorithms and data structures and formalized as concepts, analogously to the abstraction of algebraic theories in abstract algebra.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Early examples of this programming approach were implemented in Scheme and Ada, although the best known example is the Standard Template Library (STL), which developed a theory of iterators that is used to decouple sequence data structures and the algorithms operating on them.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] For example, given *N* sequence data structures, e.g. singly linked list, vector etc., and *M* algorithms to operate on them, e.g.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] `find`, `sort` etc., a direct approach would implement each algorithm specifically for each data structure, giving *N* × *M* combinations to implement.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Thus, only *N* + *M* data structure-algorithm combinations need be implemented.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] An important point is that a data structure will return a model of the most general concept that can be implemented efficiently—computational complexity requirements are explicitly part of the concept definition.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] This limits the data structures a given algorithm can be applied to and such complexity requirements are a major determinant of data structure choice.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Generic programming similarly has been applied in other domains, e.g. graph algorithms.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Although this approach often uses language features of compile-time genericity and templates, it is independent of particular language-technical details.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] — Alexander Stepanov, An Interview with A.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Other programming paradigms that have been described as generic programming include *Datatype generic programming* as described in "Generic Programming – an Introduction".
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The *Scrap your boilerplate* approach is a lightweight generic programming approach for Haskell.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] In this article we distinguish the high-level programming paradigms of *generic programming*, above, from the lower-level programming language *genericity mechanisms* used to implement them (see Programming language support for genericity).
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] For further discussion and comparison of generic programming paradigms, see.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Genericity facilities have existed in high-level languages since at least the 1970s in languages such as ML, CLU and Ada, and were subsequently adopted by many object-based and object-oriented languages, including BETA, C++, D, Eiffel, Java, and DEC's now defunct Trellis-Owl.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Genericity is implemented and supported differently in various programming languages; the term "generic" has also been used differently in various programming contexts.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] For example, in Forth the compiler can execute code while compiling and one can create new *compiler keywords* and new implementations for those words on the fly.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] It has few *words* that expose the compiler behaviour and therefore naturally offers *genericity* capacities that, however, are not referred to as such in most Forth texts.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The term has been used in functional programming, specifically in Haskell-like languages, which use a structural type system where types are always parametric and the actual code on those types is generic.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] These uses still serve a similar purpose of code-saving and rendering an abstraction.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Arrays and structs can be viewed as predefined generic types.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Every usage of an array or struct type instantiates a new concrete type, or reuses a previous instantiated type.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Array element types and struct element types are parameterized types, which are used to instantiate the corresponding generic type.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] All this is usually built-in in the compiler and the syntax differs from other generic constructs.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Some extensible programming languages try to unify built-in and user defined generic types.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] A broad survey of genericity mechanisms in programming languages follows.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] For a specific survey comparing suitability of mechanisms for generic programming, see.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] When creating container classes in statically typed languages, it is inconvenient to write specific implementations for each datatype contained, especially if the code for each datatype is virtually identical.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Above, `T` is a placeholder for whatever type is specified when the list is created.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] These "generic objects of type `T`", commonly called templates, allow a class to be reused with different datatypes as long as certain contracts such as subtypes and signature are kept.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] This genericity mechanism should not be confused with *inclusion polymorphism*, which is the algorithmic usage of exchangeable sub-classes: for instance, a list of objects of type `MovingEntity` containing objects of type `Animal` and `Car`.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The C++ `template` construct used above is widely cited as the genericity construct that popularized the notion among programmers and language designers and supports many generic programming idioms.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The D language also offers fully generic-capable templates based on the C++ precedent but with a simplified syntax.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The Java language has provided genericity facilities syntactically based on C++'s since the introduction of Java Platform, Standard Edition (J2SE) 5.0.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] C# 2.0, Oxygene 1.5 (formerly Chrome) and Visual Basic (.NET) 2005 have constructs that exploit the support for generics present in Microsoft .NET Framework since version 2.0.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Ada has had generics since it was first designed in 1977–1980.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The standard library uses generics to provide many services.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Ada 2005 adds a comprehensive generic container library to the standard library, which was inspired by C++'s Standard Template Library.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] A *generic unit* is a package or a subprogram that takes one or more *generic formal parameters*.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] A *generic formal parameter* is a value, a variable, a constant, a type, a subprogram, or even an instance of another, designated, generic unit.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] For generic formal types, the syntax distinguishes between discrete, floating-point, fixed-point, access (pointer) types, etc.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Some formal parameters can have default values.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] To *instantiate* a generic unit, the programmer passes *actual* parameters for each formal.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The generic instance then behaves just like any other unit.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] It is possible to instantiate generic units at run-time, for example, inside a loop.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The language syntax allows precise specification of constraints on generic formal parameters.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] For example, it is possible to specify that a generic formal type will only accept a modular type as the actual.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] In this example, `Array_Type` is constrained by both `Index_Type` and `Element_Type`.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] When instantiating the unit, the programmer must pass an actual array type that satisfies these constraints.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The disadvantage of this fine-grained control is a complicated syntax, but, because all generic formal parameters are completely defined in the specification, the compiler can instantiate generics without looking at the body of the generic.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Unlike C++, Ada does not allow specialised generic instances, and requires that all generics be instantiated explicitly.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] C++ uses templates to enable generic programming techniques.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The C++ Standard Library includes the Standard Template Library or STL that provides a framework of templates for common data structures and algorithms.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Templates in C++ may also be used for template metaprogramming, which is a way of pre-evaluating some of the code at compile-time rather than run-time.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Using template specialization, C++ Templates are Turing complete.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] There are many kinds of templates, the most common being function templates and class templates.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] A *function template* is a pattern for creating ordinary functions based upon the parameterizing types supplied when instantiated.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] For example, the C++ Standard Template Library contains the function template `std::max(x, y)` that creates functions that return either `x` or `y`, whichever is larger.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The compiler examines the arguments used to call `max` and determines that this is a call to `max(int, int)`.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] This works whether the arguments `x` and `y` are integers, strings, or any other type for which the expression `x < y` is sensible, or more specifically, for any type for which `operator<` is defined.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Common inheritance is not needed for the set of types that can be used, and so it is very similar to duck typing.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] A program defining a custom data type can use operator overloading to define the meaning of `<` for that type, thus allowing its use with the `std::max()` function template.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] While this may seem a minor benefit in this isolated example, in the context of a comprehensive library like the STL it allows the programmer to get extensive functionality for a new data type, just by defining a few operators for it.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Merely defining `<` allows a type to be used with the standard `std::sort()`, `std::stable_sort()`, and `std::binary_search()` algorithms or to be put inside data structures such as `std::set<T>`s (equivalent to `TreeSet<T>`, heaps, and associative arrays.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] C++ templates are completely type safe at compile time.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] As a demonstration, the standard type `std::complex<T>` does not define the `<` operator, because there is no strict order on complex numbers.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Therefore, `std::max(x, y)` will fail with a compile error, if `x` and `y` are `complex` values.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Likewise, other templates that rely on `<` cannot be applied to `complex` data unless a comparison (in the form of a functor or function) is provided.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] For instance, `std::complex<T>` cannot be used as key for a `std::map<K, V>` (equivalent to `TreeMap<K, V>`) unless a comparison is provided.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Unfortunately, compilers historically generate somewhat esoteric, long, and unhelpful error messages for this sort of error.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Ensuring that a certain object adheres to a method protocol can alleviate this issue.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Languages which use `std::compare` instead of `<` can also use `std::complex<T>` values as keys.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Another kind of template, a *class template*, extends the same concept to classes.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] A class template specialization is a class.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Class templates are often used to make generic containers.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] For example, the STL has a doubly linked list container, `std::list<T>` (equivalent to `LinkedList<T>`).
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] To make a linked list of integers, one writes `list<int>`, while a list of strings is denoted `list<string>`.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] A `std::list<T>` has a set of standard functions associated with it, that work for any compatible parameterizing types.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] C++20 introduces constraining template types using concepts.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] A powerful feature of C++'s templates is *template specialization*.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] This allows alternative implementations to be provided based on certain characteristics of the parameterized type that is being instantiated.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Template specialization has two purposes: to allow certain forms of optimization, and to reduce code bloat.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] For example, consider a `sort()` template function.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] One of the primary activities that such a function does is to swap or exchange the values in two of the container's positions.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] If the values are large (in terms of the number of bytes it takes to store each of them), then it is often quicker to first build a separate list of pointers to the objects, sort those pointers, and then build the final sorted sequence.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] If the values are quite small however it is usually fastest to just swap the values in-place as needed.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Furthermore, if the parameterized type is already of some pointer-type, then there is no need to build a separate pointer array.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Template specialization allows the template creator to write different implementations and to specify the characteristics that the parameterized type(s) must have for each implementation to be used.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Unlike function templates, class templates can be partially specialized.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] That means that an alternate version of the class template code can be provided when some of the template parameters are known, while leaving other template parameters generic.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] This can be used, for example, to create a default implementation (the *primary specialization*) that assumes that copying a parameterizing type is expensive and then create partial specializations for types that are cheap to copy, thus increasing overall efficiency.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Clients of such a class template just use specializations of it without needing to know whether the compiler used the primary specialization or some partial specialization in each case.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Class templates can also be *fully specialized,* which means that an alternate implementation can be provided when all of the parameterizing types are known.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Some uses of templates, such as the `max()` function, were formerly filled by function-like preprocessor macros (a legacy of the C language).
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Macros are expanded (copy pasted) by the preprocessor, before program compiling; templates are actual real functions.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Macros are always expanded inline; templates can also be inline functions when the compiler deems it appropriate.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] However, templates are generally considered an improvement over macros for these purposes.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Templates avoid some of the common errors found in code that makes heavy use of function-like macros, such as evaluating parameters with side effects twice.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Perhaps most importantly, templates were designed to be applicable to much larger problems than macros.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Many compilers historically had poor support for templates, thus the use of templates could make code somewhat less portable.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Support may also be poor when a C++ compiler is being used with a linker that is not C++-aware, or when attempting to use templates across shared library boundaries.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Compilers can produce confusing, long, and sometimes unhelpful error messages when errors are detected in code that uses SFINAE.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] This can make templates difficult to develop with.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Finally, the use of templates requires the compiler to generate a separate *instance* of the templated class or function for every type parameters used with it.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] (This is necessary because types in C++ are not all the same size, and the sizes of data fields are important to how classes work.) So the indiscriminate use of templates can lead to code bloat, resulting in excessively large executables.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] However, judicious use of template specialization and derivation can dramatically reduce such code bloat in some cases:So, can derivation be used to reduce the problem of code replicated because templates are used?
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] This would involve deriving a template from an ordinary class.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] This technique proved successful in curbing code bloat in real use.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Templated classes or functions may require an *explicit specialization* of the template class which would require rewriting of an entire class for a specific template parameters used by it.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The extra instantiations generated by templates can also cause some debuggers to have difficulty working gracefully with templates.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] For example, setting a debug breakpoint within a template from a source file may either miss setting the breakpoint in the actual instantiation desired or may set a breakpoint in every place the template is instantiated.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Also, the implementation source code for the template must be completely available (e.g. included in a header) to the translation unit (source file) using it.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Templates, including much of the Standard Library, if not included in header files, cannot be compiled.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] (This is in contrast to non-templated code, which may be compiled to binary, providing only a declarations header file for code using it.) This may be a disadvantage by exposing the implementing code, which removes some abstractions, and could restrict its use in closed-source projects.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The D language supports templates based in design on C++.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Templates in D use a different syntax than in C++: whereas in C++ template parameters are wrapped in angular brackets (`Template<param1, param2>`), D uses an exclamation sign and parentheses: `Template!(param1, param2)`.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] This avoids the C++ parsing difficulties due to ambiguity with comparison operators.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] If there is only one parameter, the parentheses can be omitted.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Conventionally, D combines the above features to provide compile-time polymorphism using trait-based generic programming.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Combining the above allows generating code based on existing declarations.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] For example, D serialization frameworks can enumerate a type's members and generate specialized functions for each serialized type to perform serialization and deserialization.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] User-defined attributes could further indicate serialization rules.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The `import` expression and compile-time function execution also allow efficiently implementing domain-specific languages.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Generic classes have been a part of Eiffel since the original method and language design.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The foundation publications of Eiffel, use the term *genericity* to describe creating and using generic classes.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Generic classes are declared with their class name and a list of one or more *formal generic parameters*.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The formal generic parameters are placeholders for arbitrary class names that will be supplied when a declaration of the generic class is made, as shown in the two *generic derivations* below, where `ACCOUNT` and `DEPOSIT` are other class names.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] `ACCOUNT` and `DEPOSIT` are considered *actual generic parameters* as they provide real class names to substitute for `G` in actual use.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Within the Eiffel type system, although class `LIST [G]` is considered a class, it is not considered a type.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] However, a generic derivation of `LIST [G]` such as `LIST [ACCOUNT]` is considered a type.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] For the list class shown above, an actual generic parameter substituting for `G` can be any other available class.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] To constrain the set of classes from which valid actual generic parameters can be chosen, a *generic constraint* can be specified.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] In the declaration of class `SORTED_LIST` below, the generic constraint dictates that any valid actual generic parameter will be a class that inherits from class `COMPARABLE`.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The generic constraint ensures that elements of a `SORTED_LIST` can in fact be sorted.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Support for the *generics*, or "containers-of-type-T" was added to the Java programming language in 2004 as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] In Java, generics are only checked at compile time for type correctness.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The generic type information is then removed via a process called type erasure, to maintain compatibility with old JVM implementations, making it unavailable at runtime.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] For example, a `List<String>` is converted to the raw type `java.util.List`.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The compiler inserts type casts to convert the elements to the `java.lang.String` type when they are retrieved from the list, reducing performance compared to other implementations such as C++ templates.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Generics were added as part of .NET Framework 2.0 in November 2005, based on a research prototype from Microsoft Research started in 1999.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Although similar to generics in Java, .NET generics do not apply type erasure, but implement generics as a first class mechanism in the runtime using reification.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] This design choice provides additional functionality, such as allowing reflection with preservation of generic types, and alleviating some of the limits of erasure (such as being unable to create generic arrays).
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] This also means that there is no performance hit from runtime casts and normally expensive boxing conversions.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] When primitive and value types are used as generic arguments, they get specialized implementations, allowing for efficient generic collections and methods.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] As in C++ and Java, nested generic types such as `Dictionary<string, List<int>>` are valid types, however are advised against for member signatures in code analysis design rules.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] .NET allows six varieties of generic type constraints using the `where` keyword including restricting generic types to be value types, to be classes, to have constructors, and to implement interfaces.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The `MakeAtLeast()` method allows operation on arrays, with elements of generic type `T`.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The method's type constraint indicates that the method is applicable to any type `T` that implements the generic `System.IComparable<T>` interface.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] This ensures a compile time error, if the method is called if the type does not support comparison.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The interface provides the generic method `CompareTo(T)`.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The above method could also be written without generic types, simply using the non-generic `System.Array` type.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] However, since arrays are contravariant, the casting would not be type safe, and the compiler would be unable to find certain possible errors that would otherwise be caught when using generic types.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] In addition, the method would need to access the array items as `object`s instead, and would require casting to compare two elements.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] A notable behavior of static members in a generic .NET class is static member instantiation per run-time type (see example below).
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] For Pascal, generics were first implemented in 2006, in the implementation Free Pascal.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The Object Pascal dialect Delphi acquired generics in the 2007 Delphi 11 release by CodeGear, initially only with the .NET compiler (since discontinued) before being added to the native code in the 2009 Delphi 12 release.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The semantics and abilities of Delphi generics are largely modelled on those of generics in .NET 2.0, though the implementation is by necessity quite different.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] As with C#, methods and whole types can have one or more type parameters.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] In the example, TArray is a generic type (defined by the language) and MakeAtLeast a generic method.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The available constraints are very similar to the available constraints in C#: any value type, any class, a specific class or interface, and a class with a parameterless constructor.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Multiple constraints act as an additive union.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Free Pascal implemented generics in 2006 in version 2.2.0, before Delphi and with different syntax and semantics.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] However, since FPC version 2.6.0, the Delphi-style syntax is available when using the language mode `{$mode Delphi}`.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Thus, Free Pascal code supports generics in either style.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The type class mechanism of Haskell supports generic programming.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] All the necessary methods will be "derived" – that is, constructed automatically – based on the structure of the type.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] This results in an equality function (`==`) and a string representation function (`show`) being automatically defined for any type of the form `BinTree T` provided that `T` itself supports those operations.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Ralf Hinze (2004) has shown that a similar effect can be achieved for user-defined type classes by certain programming techniques.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Other researchers have proposed approaches to this and other kinds of genericity in the context of Haskell and extensions to Haskell (discussed below).
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] PolyP was the first generic programming language extension to Haskell.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] In PolyP, generic functions are called *polytypic*.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The language introduces a special construct in which such polytypic functions can be defined via structural induction over the structure of the pattern functor of a regular datatype.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Regular datatypes in PolyP are a subset of Haskell datatypes.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] A regular datatype t must be of kind ** → **, and if *a* is the formal type argument in the definition, then all recursive calls to *t* must have the form *t a*.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] These restrictions rule out higher-kinded datatypes and nested datatypes, where the recursive calls are of a different form.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Generic Haskell is another extension to Haskell, developed at Utrecht University in the Netherlands.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] The resulting type-indexed value can be specialized to any type.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Clean offers generic programming based PolyP and the Generic Haskell as supported by the GHC ≥ 6.0.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] It parametrizes by kind as those but offers overloading.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Languages in the ML family support generic programming through parametric polymorphism and generic modules called *functors.* Both Standard ML and OCaml provide functors, which are similar to class templates and to Ada's generic packages.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Scheme syntactic abstractions also have a connection to genericity – these are in fact a superset of C++ templates.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] A Verilog module may take one or more parameters, to which their actual values are assigned upon the instantiation of the module.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] One example is a generic register array where the array width is given via a parameter.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Such an array, combined with a generic wire vector, can make a generic buffer or memory module with an arbitrary bit width out of a single module implementation.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] VHDL, being derived from Ada, also has generic abilities.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] C has a feature called "type-generic expressions" using the `_Generic` keyword: This feature gives C function overloading capabilities, but is not related to generic programming.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Generic programming can be achieved by using the preprocessor to define the generic code, with macro expansion taking the role of *instantiation*.
[src:paradigms/generic-programming] Sometimes, the non-standard extension "statement expressions" is used to simulate function-like behaviour for generic code.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] In computer science, **imperative programming** is a software programming paradigm that provides specific instructions for how computations should take place.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] This paradigm may use statements that may change a process’s state.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] In much the same way that the imperative mood in natural languages expresses commands, an imperative program consists of commands for the computer to perform.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Imperative programming focuses on describing *how* a program operates step by step (the order of the steps being generally determined in source code by the placement of statements one below the other), rather than on high-level descriptions of its expected results.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] The term is often used in contrast to declarative programming, which focuses on *what* the program should accomplish without specifying all the details of *how* the program should achieve the result.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Procedural programming is a type of imperative programming in which the program is built from one or more procedures (also termed subroutines or functions).
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] The terms are often used as synonyms, but the use of procedures has a dramatic effect on how imperative programs appear and how they are constructed.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Heavy procedural programming, in which state changes are localized to procedures or restricted to explicit arguments and returns from procedures, is a form of structured programming.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Since the 1960s, structured programming and modular programming in general have been promoted as techniques to improve the maintainability and overall quality of imperative programs.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] The concepts behind object-oriented programming attempt to extend this approach.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Procedural programming could be considered a step toward declarative programming.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] A programmer can often tell, simply by looking at the names, arguments, and return types of procedures (and related comments), what a particular procedure is supposed to do, without necessarily looking at the details of how it achieves its result.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] At the same time, a complete program is still imperative since it *fixes* the statements to be executed and their order of execution to a large extent.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] The programming paradigm used to build programs for almost all computers typically follows an imperative model.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Digital computer hardware is designed to execute machine code, which is native to the computer and is usually written in the imperative style, although low-level compilers and interpreters using other paradigms exist for some architectures such as Lisp machines.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] From this low-level perspective, the program state is defined by the contents of memory, and the statements are instructions in the native machine language of the computer.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Higher-level imperative languages use variables and more complex statements, but still follow the same paradigm.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Recipes and process checklists, while not computer programs, are also familiar concepts that are similar in style to imperative programming; each step is an instruction, and the physical world holds the state.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Since the basic ideas of imperative programming are both conceptually familiar and directly embodied in the hardware, most computer languages are in the imperative style.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Assignment statements, in imperative paradigm, perform an operation on information located in memory and store the results in memory for later use.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] High-level imperative languages, in addition, permit the evaluation of complex expressions, which may consist of a combination of arithmetic operations and function evaluations, and the assignment of the resulting value to memory.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Looping statements (as in while loops, do while loops, and for loops) allow a sequence of statements to be executed multiple times.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Loops can either execute the statements they contain a predefined number of times, or they can execute them repeatedly until some condition is met.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Conditional branching statements allow a sequence of statements to be executed only if some condition is met.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Otherwise, the statements are skipped and the execution sequence continues from the statement following them.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Unconditional branching statements allow an execution sequence to be transferred to another part of a program.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] These include the jump (called *goto* in many languages), switch, and the subprogram, subroutine, or procedure call (which usually returns to the next statement after the call).
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Early in the development of high-level programming languages, the introduction of the block enabled the construction of programs in which a group of statements and declarations could be treated as if they were one statement.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] This, alongside the introduction of subroutines, enabled complex structures to be expressed by hierarchical decomposition into simpler procedural structures.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] The earliest imperative languages were the machine languages of the original computers.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] In these languages, instructions were very simple, which made hardware implementation easier but hindered the creation of complex programs.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Fortran, developed by John Backus at International Business Machines (IBM) starting in 1954, was the first major programming language to remove the obstacles presented by machine code in the creation of complex programs.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Fortran was a compiled language that allowed named variables, complex expressions, subprograms, and many other features now common in imperative languages.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] The next two decades saw the development of many other major high-level imperative programming languages.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] In the late 1950s and 1960s, ALGOL was developed in order to allow mathematical algorithms to be more easily expressed and even served as the operating system's target language for some computers.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] MUMPS (1966) carried the imperative paradigm to a logical extreme, by not having any statements at all, relying purely on commands, even to the extent of making the IF and ELSE commands independent of each other, connected only by an intrinsic variable named $TEST.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] COBOL (1960) and BASIC (1964) were both attempts to make programming syntax look more like English.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] In the 1970s, Pascal was developed by Niklaus Wirth, and C was created by Dennis Ritchie while he was working at Bell Laboratories.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Wirth went on to design Modula-2 and Oberon.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] For the needs of the United States Department of Defense, Jean Ichbiah and a team at Honeywell began designing Ada in 1978, after a 4-year project to define the requirements for the language.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] The specification was first published in 1983, with revisions in 1995, 2005, and 2012.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] The 1980s saw a rapid growth in interest in object-oriented programming.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] These languages were imperative in style, but added features to support objects.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] The last two decades of the 20th century saw the development of many such languages.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Smalltalk-80, originally conceived by Alan Kay in 1969, was released in 1980, by the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC).
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Drawing from concepts in another object-oriented language—Simula (which is considered the world's first object-oriented programming language, developed in the 1960s)—Bjarne Stroustrup designed C++, an object-oriented language based on C.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Design of C++ began in 1979 and the first implementation was completed in 1983.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Microsoft's .NET Framework (2002) is imperative at its core, as are its main target languages, VB.NET and C# that run on it; however Microsoft's F#, a functional language, also runs on it.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Fortran (1958) was unveiled as "The IBM Mathematical FORmula TRANslating system." It was designed for scientific calculations, without string handling facilities.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] However, non-IBM vendors also wrote Fortran compilers, but with a syntax that would likely fail IBM's compiler.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) developed the first Fortran standard in 1966.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] In 1978, Fortran 77 became the standard until 1991.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] COBOL (1959) stands for "COmmon Business Oriented Language." Fortran manipulated symbols.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] It was soon realized that symbols did not need to be numbers, so strings were introduced.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] The US Department of Defense influenced COBOL's development, with Grace Hopper being a major contributor.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] The statements were English-like and verbose.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] The goal was to design a language so managers could read the programs.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] However, the lack of structured statements hindered this goal.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Development of COBOL was tightly controlled, so dialects did not emerge to require ANSI standards.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] As a consequence, it was not changed for 15 years until 1974.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] The 1990s version did make consequential changes, like object-oriented programming.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] ALGOL (1960) stands for "ALGOrithmic Language." It had a profound influence on programming language design.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Emerging from a committee of European and American programming language experts, it used standard mathematical notation and had a readable structured design.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] ALGOL was first to define its syntax using the Backus–Naur form.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] ALGOL's direct descendants include Pascal, Modula-2, Ada, Delphi and Oberon on one branch.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] On another branch there's C, C++ and Java.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] BASIC (1964) stands for "Beginner's All Purpose Symbolic Instruction Code." It was developed at Dartmouth College for all of their students to learn.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] If a student did not go on to a more powerful language, the student would still remember BASIC.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] A BASIC interpreter was installed in the microcomputers manufactured in the late 1970s.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] As the microcomputer industry grew, so did the language.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] BASIC pioneered the interactive session.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] However, the BASIC syntax was too simple for large programs.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Recent dialects added structure and object-oriented extensions.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Microsoft's Visual Basic is still widely used and produces a graphical user interface.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] C programming language (1973) got its name because the language BCPL was replaced with B, and AT&T Bell Labs called the next version "C." Its purpose was to write the UNIX operating system.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] C is a relatively small language -- making it easy to write compilers.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Its growth mirrored the hardware growth in the 1980s.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Its growth also was because it has the facilities of assembly language, but uses a high-level syntax.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] In the 1970s, software engineers needed language support to break large projects down into modules.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] One obvious feature was to decompose large projects *physically* into separate files.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] A less obvious feature was to decompose large projects *logically* into abstract datatypes.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] At the time, languages supported concrete (scalar) datatypes like integer numbers, floating-point numbers, and strings of characters.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Concrete datatypes have their representation as part of their name.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] Abstract datatypes are structures of concrete datatypes — with a new name assigned.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] For example, a list of integers could be called `integer_list`.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] In object-oriented jargon, abstract datatypes are called classes.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] However, a *class* is only a definition; no memory is allocated.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] When memory is allocated to a class, it's called an object.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] C++ (1985) was originally called "C with Classes." It was designed to expand C's capabilities by adding the object-oriented facilities of the language Simula.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] An object-oriented module is composed of two files.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] The definitions file is called the header file.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] A constructor operation is a function with the same name as the class name.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] It is executed when the calling operation executes the `new` statement.
[src:paradigms/imperative-programming] A module's other file is the *source file*.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The literate programming paradigm, as conceived by Donald Knuth, represents a move away from writing computer programs in the manner and order imposed by the compiler, and instead gives programmers macros to develop programs in the order demanded by the logic and flow of their thoughts.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Literate programs are written as an exposition of logic in more natural language in which macros are used to hide abstractions and traditional source code, more like the text of an essay.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Literate programming tools are used to obtain two representations from a source file: one understandable by a compiler or interpreter, the "tangled" code, and another for viewing as formatted documentation, which is said to be "woven" from the literate source.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] While the first generation of literate programming tools were computer language-specific, the later ones are language-agnostic and exist beyond the individual programming languages.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Literate programming was first introduced in 1984 by Donald Knuth, who intended it to create programs that were suitable literature for human beings.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] He implemented it at Stanford University as a part of his research on algorithms and digital typography.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The implementation was called "WEB" since he believed that it was one of the few three-letter words of English that had not yet been applied to computing.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] However, it resembles the complicated nature of software delicately pieced together from simple materials.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The practice of literate programming has seen an important resurgence in the 2010s with the use of computational notebooks, especially in data science.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Literate programming is writing out the program logic in a human language with included (separated by a primitive markup) code snippets and macros.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Macros in a literate source file are simply title-like or explanatory phrases in a human language that describe human abstractions created while solving the programming problem, and hiding chunks of code or lower-level macros.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] These macros are similar to the algorithms in pseudocode typically used in teaching computer science.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] These arbitrary explanatory phrases become precise new operators, created on the fly by the programmer, forming a *meta-language* on top of the underlying programming language.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] A preprocessor is used to substitute arbitrary hierarchies, or rather "interconnected 'webs' of macros", to produce the compilable source code with one command ("tangle"), and documentation with another ("weave").
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] According to Knuth, literate programming provides higher-quality programs, since it forces programmers to explicitly state the thoughts behind the program, making poorly thought-out design decisions more obvious.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Knuth also claims that literate programming provides a first-rate documentation system, which is not an add-on, but is grown naturally in the process of exposition of one's thoughts during a program's creation.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The resulting documentation allows the author to restart their own thought processes at any later time, and allows other programmers to understand the construction of the program more easily.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] This differs from traditional documentation, in which a programmer is presented with source code that follows a compiler-imposed order, and must decipher the thought process behind the program from the code and its associated comments.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The meta-language capabilities of literate programming are also claimed to facilitate thinking, giving a higher "bird's eye view" of the code and increasing the number of concepts the mind can successfully retain and process.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Applicability of the concept to programming on a large scale, that of commercial-grade programs, is proven by an edition of TeX code as a literate program.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Knuth also claims that literate programming can lead to easy porting of software to multiple environments, and even cites the implementation of TeX as an example.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Literate programming is very often misunderstood to refer only to formatted documentation produced from a common file with both source code and comments – which is properly called documentation generation – or to voluminous commentaries included with code.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] This misconception has led to claims that comment-extraction tools, such as the Perl Plain Old Documentation or Java Javadoc systems, are "literate programming tools".
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Weaving and tangling are done on the same source so that they are consistent with each other.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] A classic example of literate programming is the literate implementation of the standard Unix `wc` word counting program.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Knuth presented a CWEB version of this example in Chapter 12 of his *Literate Programming* book.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The same example was later rewritten for the noweb literate programming tool.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] This example provides a good illustration of the basic elements of literate programming.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The following snippet of the `wc` literate program shows how arbitrary descriptive phrases in a natural language are used in a literate program to create macros, which act as new "operators" in the literate programming language, and hide chunks of code or other macros.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The mark-up notation consists of double angle brackets (`<<...>>`) that indicate macros.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The `@` symbol which, in a noweb file, indicates the beginning of a documentation chunk.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The `<<*>>` symbol stands for the "root", topmost node the literate programming tool will start expanding the web of macros from.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Actually, writing out the expanded source code can be done from any section or subsection (i.e. a piece of code designated as `<<name of the chunk>>=`, with the equal sign), so one literate program file can contain several files with machine source code.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The unraveling of the chunks can be done in any place in the literate program text file, not necessarily in the order they are sequenced in the enclosing chunk, but as is demanded by the logic reflected in the explanatory text that envelops the whole program.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Macros are not the same as "section names" in standard documentation.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Literate programming macros hide the real code behind themselves, and be used inside any low-level machine language operators, often inside logical operators such as `if`, `while` or `case`.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] This can be seen in the following `wc` literate program.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The macros stand for any chunk of code or other macros, and are more general than top-down or bottom-up "chunking", or than subsectioning.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Donald Knuth said that when he realized this, he began to think of a program as a *web* of various parts.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The documentation for a literate program is produced as part of writing the program.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Instead of comments provided as side notes to source code a literate program contains the explanation of concepts on each level, with lower level concepts deferred to their appropriate place, which allows better communication of thought.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The snippets of the literate `wc` above show how an explanation of the program and its source code are interwoven.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Such exposition of ideas creates the flow of thought that is like a literary work.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Knuth wrote a "novel" which explains the code of the interactive fiction game Colossal Cave Adventure.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The first published literate programming environment was WEB, introduced by Knuth in 1981 for his TeX typesetting system; it uses Pascal as its underlying programming language and TeX for typesetting of the documentation.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The complete commented TeX source code was published in Knuth's *TeX: The program*, volume B of his 5-volume *Computers and Typesetting*.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Knuth had privately used a literate programming system called DOC as early as 1979.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] He was inspired by the ideas of Pierre-Arnoul de Marneffe.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] The free CWEB, written by Knuth and Silvio Levy, is WEB adapted for C and C++, runs on most operating systems, and can produce TeX and PDF documentation.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] There are various other implementations of the literate programming concept as given below.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] Many of the newer among these do not have macros and hence do not comply with the order of human logic principle, which makes them perhaps "semi-literate" tools.
[src:paradigms/literate-programming] These, however, allow cellular execution of code which makes them more along the lines of exploratory programming tools.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] `A` is called the *head* of the rule, `B1`, ..., `Bn` is called the *body*, and the `Bi` are called *literals* or conditions.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In the simplest case of Horn clauses (or "definite" clauses), all of the A, B1, ..., Bn are atomic formulae of the form p(t1 ,..., tm), where p is a predicate symbol naming a relation, like "motherhood", and the ti are terms naming objects (or individuals).
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Terms include both constant symbols, like "charles", and variables, such as X, which start with an upper case letter.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Given a query, the program produces answers.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] For instance the program can be queried both to generate grandparents and to generate grandchildren.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Although Horn clause logic programs are Turing complete, for most practical applications, Horn clause programs need to be extended to "normal" logic programs with negative conditions.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Logic programming languages that include negative conditions have the knowledge representation capabilities of a non-monotonic logic.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In ASP and Datalog, logic programs have only a declarative reading, and their execution is performed by means of a proof procedure or model generator whose behaviour is not meant to be controlled by the programmer.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] However, in the Prolog family of languages, logic programs also have a procedural interpretation as goal-reduction procedures.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Negative conditions in the bodies of clauses also have a procedural interpretation, known as *negation as failure*: A negative literal `not B` is deemed to hold if and only if the positive literal `B` fails to hold.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Much of the research in the field of logic programming has been concerned with trying to develop a logical semantics for negation as failure and with developing other semantics and other implementations for negation.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] These developments have been important, in turn, for supporting the development of formal methods for logic-based program verification and program transformation.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The use of mathematical logic to represent and execute computer programs is also a feature of the lambda calculus, developed by Alonzo Church in the 1930s.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] However, the first proposal to use the clausal form of logic for representing computer programs was made by Cordell Green.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] This used an axiomatization of a subset of LISP, together with a representation of an input-output relation, to compute the relation by simulating the execution of the program in LISP.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Foster and Elcock's Absys, on the other hand, employed a combination of equations and lambda calculus in an assertional programming language that places no constraints on the order in which operations are performed.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Logic programming, with its current syntax of facts and rules, can be traced back to debates in the late 1960s and early 1970s about declarative versus procedural representations of knowledge in artificial intelligence.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Advocates of declarative representations were notably working at Stanford, associated with John McCarthy, Bertram Raphael, and Cordell Green, and in Edinburgh, with John Alan Robinson (an academic visitor from Syracuse University), Pat Hayes, and Robert Kowalski.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Advocates of procedural representations were mainly centered at MIT, under the leadership of Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Although it was based on the proof methods of logic, Planner, developed by Carl Hewitt at MIT, was the first language to emerge within this proceduralist paradigm.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Planner featured pattern-directed invocation of procedural plans from goals (i.e. goal-reduction or backward chaining) and from assertions (i.e. forward chaining).
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The most influential implementation of Planner was the subset of Planner, called Micro-Planner, implemented by Gerry Sussman, Eugene Charniak, and Terry Winograd.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Winograd used Micro-Planner to implement the landmark, natural-language understanding program SHRDLU.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] For the sake of efficiency, Planner used a backtracking control structure so that only one possible computation path had to be stored at a time.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Planner gave rise to the programming languages QA4, Popler, Conniver, QLISP, and the concurrent language Ether.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Hayes and Kowalski in Edinburgh tried to reconcile the logic-based declarative approach to knowledge representation with Planner's procedural approach.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Hayes (1973) developed an equational language, Golux, in which different procedures could be obtained by altering the behavior of the theorem prover.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In the meanwhile, Alain Colmerauer in Marseille was working on natural-language understanding, using logic to represent semantics and using resolution for question-answering.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] During the summer of 1971, Colmerauer invited Kowalski to Marseille, and together they discovered that the clausal form of logic could be used to represent formal grammars and that resolution theorem provers could be used for parsing.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] They observed that some theorem provers, like hyper-resolution, behave as bottom-up parsers and others, like SL resolution (1971) behave as top-down parsers.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] It was in the following summer of 1972, that Kowalski, again working with Colmerauer, developed the procedural interpretation of implications in clausal form.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] It also became clear that such clauses could be restricted to definite clauses or Horn clauses, and that SL-resolution could be restricted (and generalised) to SLD resolution.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Kowalski's procedural interpretation and SLD were described in a 1973 memo, published in 1974.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Colmerauer, with Philippe Roussel, used the procedural interpretation as the basis of Prolog, which was implemented in the summer and autumn of 1972.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The first Prolog program, also written in 1972 and implemented in Marseille, was a French question-answering system.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The use of Prolog as a practical programming language was given great momentum by the development of a compiler by David H.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Experiments demonstrated that Edinburgh Prolog could compete with the processing speed of other symbolic programming languages such as Lisp.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Edinburgh Prolog became the *de facto* standard and strongly influenced the definition of ISO standard Prolog.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Logic programming gained international attention during the 1980s, when it was chosen by the Japanese Ministry of International Trade and Industry to develop the software for the Fifth Generation Computer Systems (FGCS) project.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The FGCS project aimed to use logic programming to develop advanced Artificial Intelligence applications on massively parallel computers.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Although the project initially explored the use of Prolog, it later adopted the use of concurrent logic programming, because it was closer to the FGCS computer architecture.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] However, the committed choice feature of concurrent logic programming interfered with the language's logical semantics and with its suitability for knowledge representation and problem solving applications.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Moreover, the parallel computer systems developed in the project failed to compete with advances taking place in the development of more conventional, general-purpose computers.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Together these two issues resulted in the FGCS project failing to meet its objectives.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Interest in both logic programming and AI fell into world-wide decline.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In the meanwhile, more declarative logic programming approaches, including those based on the use of Prolog, continued to make progress independently of the FGCS project.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In particular, although Prolog was developed to combine declarative and procedural representations of knowledge, the purely declarative interpretation of logic programs became the focus for applications in the field of deductive databases.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Work in this field became prominent around 1977, when Hervé Gallaire and Jack Minker organized a workshop on logic and databases in Toulouse.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The field was eventually renamed as *Datalog*.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] This focus on the logical, declarative reading of logic programs was given further impetus by the development of constraint logic programming in the 1980s and Answer Set Programming in the 1990s.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The Association for Logic Programming (ALP) was founded in 1986 to promote Logic Programming.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Its official journal until 2000, was *The Journal of Logic Programming*.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In 2001, the journal was renamed *The Journal of Logic and Algebraic Programming*, and the official journal of ALP became *Theory and Practice of Logic Programming*, published by Cambridge University Press.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Logic programs enjoy a rich variety of semantics and problem solving methods, as well as a wide range of applications in programming, databases, knowledge representation, and problem solving.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The procedural interpretation of logic programs, which uses backward reasoning to reduce goals to subgoals, is a special case of the use of a problem-solving strategy to **control** the use of a declarative, **logical** representation of knowledge to obtain the behaviour of an **algorithm**.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] More generally, different problem-solving strategies can be applied to the same logical representation to obtain different algorithms.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Alternatively, different algorithms can be obtained with a given problem-solving strategy by using different logical representations.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The two main problem-solving strategies are backward reasoning (goal reduction) and forward reasoning, also known as top-down and bottom-up reasoning, respectively.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In the simple case of a propositional Horn clause program and a top-level atomic goal, backward reasoning determines an and-or tree, which constitutes the search space for solving the goal.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The top-level goal is the root of the tree.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Given any node in the tree and any clause whose head matches the node, there exists a set of child nodes corresponding to the sub-goals in the body of the clause.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] These child nodes are grouped together by an "and".
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The alternative sets of children corresponding to alternative ways of solving the node are grouped together by an "or".
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Any search strategy can be used to search this space.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Prolog uses a sequential, last-in-first-out, backtracking strategy, in which only one alternative and one sub-goal are considered at a time.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] For example, subgoals can be solved in parallel, and clauses can also be tried in parallel.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The first strategy is called **and-parallel** and the second strategy is called **or-parallel**.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Other search strategies, such as intelligent backtracking, or best-first search to find an optimal solution, are also possible.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In the more general, non-propositional case, where sub-goals can share variables, other strategies can be used, such as choosing the subgoal that is most highly instantiated or that is sufficiently instantiated so that only one procedure applies.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Such strategies are used, for example, in concurrent logic programming.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In most cases, backward reasoning from a query or goal is more efficient than forward reasoning.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] But sometimes with Datalog and Answer Set Programming, there may be no query that is separate from the set of clauses as a whole, and then generating all the facts that can be derived from the clauses is a sensible problem-solving strategy.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Here the relation `fibonacci(N, M)` stands for the function `fibonacci(N) = M`, and the predicate `N is Expression` is Prolog notation for the predicate that instantiates the variable `N` to the value of `Expression`.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Given the goal of computing the fibonacci number of `n`, backward reasoning reduces the goal to the two subgoals of computing the fibonacci numbers of n-1 and n-2.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] It reduces the subgoal of computing the fibonacci number of n-1 to the two subgoals of computing the fibonacci numbers of n-2 and n-3, redundantly computing the fibonacci number of n-2.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] This process of reducing one fibonacci subgoal to two fibonacci subgoals continues until it reaches the numbers 0 and 1.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In contrast, forward reasoning generates the sequence of fibonacci numbers, starting from 0 and 1 without any recomputation, and its complexity is linear with respect to n.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Prolog cannot perform forward reasoning directly.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] But it can achieve the effect of forward reasoning within the context of backward reasoning by means of tabling: Subgoals are maintained in a table, along with their solutions.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] If a subgoal is re-encountered, it is solved directly by using the solutions already in the table, instead of re-solving the subgoals redundantly.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In this respect, logic programs are similar to relational databases, which also represent functions as relations.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Compared with relational syntax, functional syntax is more compact for nested functions.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] However, nested syntax can be regarded as syntactic sugar for unnested syntax.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Ciao Prolog, for example, transforms functional syntax into relational form and executes the resulting logic program using the standard Prolog execution strategy.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Moreover, the same transformation can be used to execute nested relations that are not functional.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The term *relational programming* has been used to cover a variety of programming languages that treat functions as a special case of relations.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Some of these languages, such as miniKanren and relational linear programming are logic programming languages in the sense of this article.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] However, the relational language RML is an imperative programming language whose core construct is a relational expression, which is similar to an expression in first-order predicate logic.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Other relational programming languages are based on the relational calculus or relational algebra.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Viewed in purely logical terms, there are two approaches to the declarative semantics of Horn clause logic programs: One approach is the original *logical consequence semantics*, which understands solving a goal as showing that the goal is a theorem that is true in all models of the program.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In this approach, computation is theorem-proving in first-order logic; and both backward reasoning, as in SLD resolution, and forward reasoning, as in hyper-resolution, are correct and complete theorem-proving methods.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Sometimes such theorem-proving methods are also regarded as providing a separate proof-theoretic (or operational) semantics for logic programs.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] But from a logical point of view, they are proof methods, rather than semantics.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The other approach to the declarative semantics of Horn clause programs is the *satisfiability semantics*, which understands solving a goal as showing that the goal is true (or satisfied) in some intended (or standard) model of the program.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] For Horn clause programs, there always exists such a standard model: It is the unique *minimal model* of the program.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Informally speaking, a minimal model is a model that, when it is viewed as the set of all (variable-free) facts that are true in the model, contains no smaller set of facts that is also a model of the program.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] For example, the following facts represent the minimal model of the family relationships example in the introduction of this article.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The satisfiability semantics also has an alternative, more mathematical characterisation as the least fixed point of the function that uses the rules in the program to derive new facts from existing facts in one step of inference.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Backward reasoning, which succeeds by reducing a goal to subgoals, until all subgoals are solved by facts, ensures that the goal is true in the minimal model, without generating the model explicitly.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The difference between the two declarative semantics can be seen with the definitions of addition and multiplication in successor arithmetic, which represents the natural numbers `0, 1, 2, ...` as a sequence of terms of the form `0, s(0), s(s(0)), ...`.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The two declarative semantics both give the same answers for the same existentially quantified conjunctions of addition and multiplication goals.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] However, with the logical-consequence semantics, there are non-standard models of the program, in which, for example, `add(s(s(0)), s(s(0)), s(s(s(s(s(0)))))),` i.e.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] But with the satisfiability semantics, there is only one model, namely the standard model of arithmetic, in which `2 + 2 = 5` is false.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In the satisfiability semantics, the failure of the goal means that the truth value of the goal is false.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] But in the logical consequence semantics, the failure means that the truth value of the goal is unknown.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Negation as failure (NAF), as a way of concluding that a negative condition `not p` holds by showing that the positive condition `p` fails to hold, was already a feature of early Prolog systems.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The resulting extension of SLD resolution is called SLDNF.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] A similar construct, called "thnot", also existed in Micro-Planner.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The logical semantics of NAF was unresolved until Keith Clark showed that, under certain natural conditions, NAF is an efficient, correct (and sometimes complete) way of reasoning with the logical consequence semantics using the *completion* of a logic program in first-order logic.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The completion also includes axioms of equality, which correspond to unification.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Clark showed that proofs generated by SLDNF are structurally similar to proofs generated by a natural deduction style of reasoning with the completion of the program.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] This is because tom is a thief, and it cannot be shown that tom should be rehabilitated.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] It cannot be shown that tom should be rehabilitated, because it cannot be shown that tom is a minor.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] This property of withdrawing a conclusion when new information is added, is called non-monotonicity, and it makes logic programming a non-monotonic logic.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The notion of completion is closely related to John McCarthy's circumscription semantics for default reasoning, and to Ray Reiter's closed world assumption.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The completion semantics for negation is a logical consequence semantics, for which SLDNF provides a proof-theoretic implementation.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] However, in the 1980s, the satisfiability semantics became more popular for logic programs with negation.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In the satisfiability semantics, negation is interpreted according to the classical definition of truth in an intended or standard model of the logic program.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In the case of logic programs with negative conditions, there are two main variants of the satisfiability semantics: In the well-founded semantics, the intended model of a logic program is a unique, three-valued, minimal model, which always exists.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The well-founded semantics generalises the notion of inductive definition in mathematical logic.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] XSB Prolog implements the well-founded semantics using SLG resolution.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In the alternative stable model semantics, there may be no intended models or several intended models, all of which are minimal and two-valued.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The stable model semantics underpins answer set programming (ASP).
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Both the well-founded and stable model semantics apply to arbitrary logic programs with negation.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] However, both semantics coincide for stratified logic programs.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Attempts to understand negation in logic programming have also contributed to the development of abstract argumentation frameworks.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In an argumentation interpretation of negation, the initial argument that tom should be punished because he is a thief, is attacked by the argument that he should be rehabilitated because he is a minor.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] But the fact that tom is violent undermines the argument that tom should be rehabilitated and reinstates the argument that tom should be punished.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Metaprogramming, in which programs are treated as data, was already a feature of early Prolog implementations.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] For example, the Edinburgh DEC10 implementation of Prolog included "an interpreter and a compiler, both written in Prolog itself".
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] where true represents an empty conjunction, and (B,C) is a composite term representing the conjunction of B and C.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The predicate clause(A,B) means that there is a clause of the form A :- B.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Metaprogramming is an application of the more general use of a *metalogic* or *metalanguage* to describe and reason about another language, called the *object language*.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Metalogic programming allows object-level and metalevel representations to be combined, as in natural language.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In his popular Introduction to Cognitive Science, Paul Thagard includes logic and rules as alternative approaches to modelling human thinking.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] He argues that rules, which have the form *IF condition THEN action*, are "very similar" to logical conditionals, but they are simpler and have greater psychological plausibility (page 51).
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Among other differences between logic and rules, he argues that logic uses deduction, but rules use search (page 45) and can be used to reason either forward or backward (page 47).
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Sentences in logic "have to be interpreted as *universally true*", but rules can be *defaults*, which admit exceptions (page 44).
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] He states that "unlike logic, rule-based systems can also easily represent strategic information about what to do" (page 45).
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] For example, "IF you want to go home for the weekend, and you have bus fare, THEN you can catch a bus".
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] All of these characteristics of rule-based systems - search, forward and backward reasoning, default reasoning, and goal-reduction - are also defining characteristics of logic programming.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Other arguments showing how logic programming can be used to model aspects of human thinking are presented by Keith Stenning and Michiel van Lambalgen in their book, Human Reasoning and Cognitive Science.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] They show how the non-monotonic character of logic programs can be used to explain human performance on a variety of psychological tasks.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] In The Proper Treatment of Events, Michiel van Lambalgen and Fritz Hamm investigate the use of constraint logic programming to code "temporal notions in natural language by looking at the way human beings construct time".
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The use of logic to represent procedural knowledge and strategic information was one of the main goals contributing to the early development of logic programming.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Moreover, it continues to be an important feature of the Prolog family of logic programming languages today.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] However, many applications of logic programming, including Prolog applications, increasingly focus on the use of logic to represent purely declarative knowledge.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] These applications include both the representation of general commonsense knowledge and the representation of domain specific expertise.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Commonsense includes knowledge about cause and effect, as formalised, for example, in the situation calculus, event calculus and action languages.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Here is a simplified example, which illustrates the main features of such formalisms.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The first clause states that a fact holds immediately after an event initiates (or causes) the fact.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The second clause is a *frame axiom*, which states that a fact that holds at a time continues to hold at the next time unless it is terminated by an event that happens at the time.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Here `holds` is a meta-predicate, similar to `solve` above.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] However, whereas `solve` has only one argument, which applies to general clauses, the first argument of `holds` is a fact and the second argument is a time (or state).
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The atomic formula `holds(Fact, Time)` expresses that the `Fact` holds at the `Time`.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Such time-varying facts are also called fluents.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The atomic formula `happens(Event, Time)` expresses that the Event happens at the `Time`.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] The following example illustrates how these clauses can be used to reason about causality in a toy blocks world.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Here, in the initial state at time 0, a green block is on a table and a red block is stacked on the green block (like a traffic light).
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] At time 0, the red block is moved to the table.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] At time 1, the green block is moved onto the red block.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Forward reasoning and backward reasoning generate the same answers to the goal `holds(Fact, Time)`.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] But forward reasoning generates fluents *progressively* in temporal order, and backward reasoning generates fluents *regressively*, as in the domain-specific use of regression in the situation calculus.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] Logic programming has also proved to be useful for representing domain-specific expertise in expert systems.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] But human expertise, like general-purpose commonsense, is mostly implicit and tacit, and it is often difficult to represent such implicit knowledge in explicit rules.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] This difficulty does not arise, however, when logic programs are used to represent the existing, explicit rules of a business organisation or legal authority.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p01] More recently, the PROLEG system, initiated in 2009 and consisting of approximately 2500 rules and exceptions of civil code and supreme court case rules in Japan, has become possibly the largest legal rule base in the world.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] The SLD resolution rule of inference is neutral about the order in which subgoals in the bodies of clauses can be *selected* for solution.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] For the sake of efficiency, Prolog restricts this order to the order in which the subgoals are written.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] SLD is also neutral about the strategy for searching the space of SLD proofs.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Prolog searches this space, top-down, depth-first, trying different clauses for solving the same (sub)goal in the order in which the clauses are written.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] This search strategy has the advantage that the current branch of the tree can be represented efficiently by a stack.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] When a goal clause at the top of the stack is reduced to a new goal clause, the new goal clause is pushed onto the top of the stack.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Backtracking can be restricted by using a subgoal, called *cut*, written as !, which always succeeds but cannot be backtracked.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Cut can be used to improve efficiency, but can also interfere with the logical meaning of clauses.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] In many cases, the use of cut can be replaced by negation as failure.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Prolog provides other features, in addition to cut, that do not have a logical interpretation.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] These include the built-in predicates *assert* and *retract* for destructively updating the state of the program during program execution.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Various extensions of logic programming have been developed to provide a logical framework for such destructive change of state.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] The broad range of Prolog applications, both in isolation and in combination with other languages is highlighted in the Year of Prolog Book, celebrating the 50 year anniversary of Prolog in 2022.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Prolog has also contributed to the development of other programming languages, including ALF, Fril, Gödel, Mercury, Oz, Ciao, Visual Prolog, XSB, and λProlog.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Constraint logic programming (CLP) combines Horn clause logic programming with constraint solving.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] It extends Horn clauses by allowing some predicates, declared as constraint predicates, to occur as literals in the body of a clause.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Constraint predicates are not defined by the facts and rules in the program, but are predefined by some domain-specific model-theoretic structure or theory.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Procedurally, subgoals whose predicates are defined by the program are solved by goal-reduction, as in ordinary logic programming, but constraints are simplified and checked for satisfiability by a domain-specific constraint-solver, which implements the semantics of the constraint predicates.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] An initial problem is solved by reducing it to a satisfiable conjunction of constraints.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Interestingly, the first version of Prolog already included a constraint predicate dif(term1, term2), from Philippe Roussel's 1972 PhD thesis, which succeeds if both of its arguments are different terms, but which is delayed if either of the terms contains a variable.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Here `≤` and `<` are constraint predicates, with their usual intended semantics.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Constraint logic programming has been used to solve problems in such fields as civil engineering, mechanical engineering, digital circuit verification, automated timetabling, air traffic control, and finance.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] It is closely related to abductive logic programming.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Datalog is a database definition language, which combines a relational view of data, as in relational databases, with a logical view, as in logic programming.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Relational databases use a relational calculus or relational algebra, with relational operations, such as *union*, *intersection*, *set difference* and *cartesian product* to specify queries, which access a database.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Datalog uses logical connectives, such as *or*, *and* and *not* in the bodies of rules to define relations as part of the database itself.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] It was recognized early in the development of relational databases that recursive queries cannot be expressed in either relational algebra or relational calculus, and that this deficiency can be remedied by introducing a least-fixed-point operator.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] In contrast, recursive relations can be defined naturally by rules in logic programs, without the need for any new logical connectives or operators.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Datalog differs from more general logic programming by having only constants and variables as terms.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Moreover, all facts are variable-free, and rules are restricted, so that if they are executed bottom-up, then the derived facts are also variable-free.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] However, top-down execution with tabling gives the same answers and terminates without looping.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Like Datalog, Answer Set programming (ASP) is not Turing-complete.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Moreover, instead of separating goals (or queries) from the program to be used in solving the goals, ASP treats the whole program as a goal, and solves the goal by generating a stable model that makes the goal true.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] For this purpose, it uses the stable model semantics, according to which a logic program can have zero, one or more intended models.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] To represent the standard version of the map colouring problem, we need to add a constraint that two adjacent countries cannot be coloured the same colour.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] The addition of constraints of the form `:- Body.` eliminates models in which `Body` is true.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Confusingly, *constraints in ASP* are different from *constraints in CLP*.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Constraints in CLP are predicates that qualify answers to queries (and solutions of goals).
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Constraints in ASP are clauses that eliminate models that would otherwise satisfy goals.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Constraints in ASP are like integrity constraints in databases.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] This combination of ordinary logic programming clauses and constraint clauses illustrates the generate-and-test methodology of problem solving in ASP: The ordinary clauses define a search space of possible solutions, and the constraints filter out unwanted solutions.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Most implementations of ASP proceed in two steps: First they instantiate the program in all possible ways, reducing it to a propositional logic program (known as *grounding*).
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Then they apply a propositional logic problem solver, such as the DPLL algorithm or a Boolean SAT solver.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] However, some implementations, such as s(CASP) use a goal-directed, top-down, SLD resolution-like procedure without grounding.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Abductive logic programming (ALP), like CLP, extends normal logic programming by allowing the bodies of clauses to contain literals whose predicates are not defined by clauses.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] In ALP, these predicates are declared as *abducible* (or *assumable*), and are used as in abductive reasoning to explain observations, or more generally to add new facts to the program (as assumptions) to solve goals.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] The goal can represent an observation, in which case a solution is an explanation of the observation.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Or the goal can represent a desired future state of affairs, in which case a solution is a plan for achieving the goal.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] ALP solves the goal by reasoning backwards and adding assumptions to the program, to solve abducible subgoals.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Here `tick` is an event that marks the passage of time without initiating or terminating any fluents.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] There are also solutions in which the two `move` events happen at the same time.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Abductive logic programming has been used for fault diagnosis, planning, natural language processing and machine learning.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] It has also been used to interpret negation as failure as a form of abductive reasoning.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Inductive logic programming (ILP) is an approach to machine learning that induces logic programs as hypothetical generalisations of positive and negative examples.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Given a logic program representing background knowledge and positive examples together with constraints representing negative examples, an ILP system induces a logic program that generalises the positive examples while excluding the negative examples.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] ILP is similar to ALP, in that both can be viewed as generating hypotheses to explain observations, and as employing constraints to exclude undesirable hypotheses.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] But in ALP the hypotheses are variable-free facts, and in ILP the hypotheses are general rules.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Stuart Russell has referred to such invention of new concepts as the most important step needed for reaching human-level AI.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Recent work in ILP, combining logic programming, learning and probability, has given rise to the fields of statistical relational learning and probabilistic inductive logic programming.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Concurrent logic programming integrates concepts of logic programming with concurrent programming.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Its development was given a big impetus in the 1980s by its choice for the systems programming language of the Japanese Fifth Generation Project (FGCS).
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] The conjunction `G1, ... , Gn` is called the guard of the clause, and | is the commitment operator.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] However, procedurally, when there are several clauses whose heads `H` match a given goal, then all of the clauses are executed in parallel, checking whether their guards `G1, ... , Gn` hold.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] If the guards of more than one clause hold, then a committed choice is made to one of the clauses, and execution proceeds with the subgoals `B1, ..., Bn` of the chosen clause.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] These subgoals can also be executed in parallel.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Thus concurrent logic programming implements a form of "don't care nondeterminism", rather than "don't know nondeterminism".
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Here, `[]` represents the empty list, and `[Head | Tail]` represents a list with first element `Head` followed by list `Tail`, as in Prolog.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] The program will non-deterministically generate a single solution, for example `Merge = [ace, queen, 1, king, 4, 2]`.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Carl Hewitt has argued that, because of the indeterminacy of concurrent computation, concurrent logic programming cannot implement general concurrency.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] However, according to the logical semantics, any result of a computation of a concurrent logic program is a logical consequence of the program, even though not all logical consequences can be derived.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Concurrent constraint logic programming combines concurrent logic programming and constraint logic programming, using constraints to control concurrency.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] A clause can contain a guard, which is a set of constraints that may block the applicability of the clause.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] When the guards of several clauses are satisfied, concurrent constraint logic programming makes a committed choice to use only one.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Several researchers have extended logic programming with higher-order programming features derived from higher-order logic, such as predicate variables.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Such languages include the Prolog extensions HiLog and λProlog.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Basing logic programming within linear logic has resulted in the design of logic programming languages that are considerably more expressive than those based on classical logic.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Horn clause programs can only represent state change by the change in arguments to predicates.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] In linear logic programming, one can use the ambient linear logic to support state change.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Some early designs of logic programming languages based on linear logic include LO, Lolli, ACL, and Forum.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Forum provides a goal-directed interpretation of all linear logic.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] F-logic extends logic programming with objects and the frame syntax.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Logtalk extends the Prolog programming language with support for objects, protocols, and other OOP concepts.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] It supports most standard-compliant Prolog systems as backend compilers.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] Transaction logic is an extension of logic programming with a logical theory of state-modifying updates.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] It has both a model-theoretic semantics and a procedural one.
[src:paradigms/logic-programming-p02] An implementation of a subset of Transaction logic is available in the Flora-2 system.
[src:paradigms/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming can be used to move computations from runtime to compile time, to generate code using compile time computations, and to enable self-modifying code.
[src:paradigms/metaprogramming] The ability of a programming language to be its own metalanguage allows reflective programming, and is termed *reflection*.
[src:paradigms/metaprogramming] Reflection is a valuable language feature to facilitate metaprogramming.
[src:paradigms/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming was popular in the 1970s and 1980s using list processing languages such as Lisp.
[src:paradigms/metaprogramming] Lisp machine hardware gained some notice in the 1980s, and enabled applications that could process code.
[src:paradigms/metaprogramming] They were often used for artificial intelligence applications.
[src:paradigms/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming enables developers to write programs and develop code that falls under the generic programming paradigm.
[src:paradigms/metaprogramming] Having the programming language itself as a first-class data type (as in Lisp, Prolog, SNOBOL, or Rebol) is also very useful; this is known as *homoiconicity*.
[src:paradigms/metaprogramming] Generic programming invokes a metaprogramming facility within a language by allowing one to write code without the concern of specifying data types since they can be supplied as parameters when used.
[src:paradigms/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming usually works in one of three ways.
